Individuals with autism may find maintaining eye contact uncomfortable or overwhelming, which can affect social interactions. This aversion to eye contact is often due to the intense sensory input it involves, making it hard to process simultaneously with conversation. Seeking time alone is another common trait, as social situations can be exhausting and overstimulating. Personal space provides a refuge where individuals can decompress and engage in self-soothing activities, away from the unpredictability of social demands. Language comprehension in autism can be notably literal. Metaphors, idioms, and sarcasm are often taken at face value, as the nuanced and abstract nature of these expressions can be challenging to interpret. This literal understanding reflects a different cognitive processing style, emphasizing concrete over abstract thinking. Sensory hypersensitivity means that ordinary stimuli, such as lights, sounds, textures, or smells, can be overwhelmingly intense. This heightened sensitivity can lead to discomfort or distress in environments that are otherwise considered normal, necessitating careful management to ensure comfort and reduce anxiety. These features collectively illustrate the diverse and individualised nature of autism, shaping how each person experiences and interacts with the world. #autism #asd #autismawareness #mentalhealth #psychiatry #psychiatrist

Part of it has to do with what people seem to expect of us without having any idea what goes into each day or what we have to consider when we do things outside of our daily routine. I made a mistake , I wish I could turn back the hands of time , I never would have introduced Tv to my baby . I hope first time moms can learn from this . Excessive screen time causes developmental delays and regression and Autism like behaviors (virtual Autism) . Zayne has been exposed to excessive screentime because it helped me have time for myself or when i would get busy with school work and other things , screentime was my go to , to keep him calm while i got things done .  This is an action im regretting so much .. Im retracting my steps to cutting down Zayne’s screen time and engaging more activities with him and this has been tough & heartbreaking, he’s been throwing meltdown and tantrums  because hes not getting what he wants , i have tried everything to calm him down , he’s just super upset . I had to let him cry it out .I expected this reaction from him . I cant wait for us to pass this stage .  If you have any advice to help make this process easier for us please leave them in the comments, ill be reading them  . . #fypviralシviral #tiktoknigeria🇳🇬 #babytiktok #foryoupage #momsoftiktok

Not everyone will accept, let alone understand. Not every neighborhood will welcome us, be it renting or even owning. Still a long way to go before we can have a society that practices inclusivity. There are still too many things that are not meant for people like us with our son's conditions. Rigid rules and regulations that were set wihout having people like us with limitations in mind. It is what it is. We’re like the X-MEN in many ways. The fight must go on... Tidak semua orang akan menerima, apatah lagi memahami. Tidak setiap kejiranan akan menyambut kami, sama ada menyewa atau memiliki. Jauh lagi perjalanannya  untuk wujudkan satu masyarakat yang betul mengamalkan inklusiviti. Akan ada situasi atau benda yang tidak sesuai untuk orang seperti kami yang ada anak seperti Adam. Inilah kenyataannya. Kami ibarat X-MEN... Perjuangan perlu diteruskan. #adamsautismfamily #autism #autisme #selfregulation #stimming #autismacceptance #inclusivity #xmen

Charles é um milagre. Lutou muito para viver!! Um vencedor. Hoje ele tem 16 anos. Meu amor. Meu anjo azul 💙💙🙏🙏 Sobre o Charles: Nosso menino que nasceu prematuro extremo, que ficou 4 meses lutando pela vida em uma UTI. Que fez cirurgia cardíaca apenas com nove dias. Não pesava nem um quilo. Ficou entubado e passou por milhões de procedimentos. Voltou depois aos oito meses de novo para a UTI. Mais uma luta pela vida. Em casa passou por muita fisioterapia. Vários tipos de terapia que ele precisava. Precisou de ajuda para aprender a rolar, sentar, andar e falar. Pois o lado do cérebro que nos faz aprender sozinhos tudo isso nele não funciona. Depois que ele teve alta minha casa parecia outro hospital. Esse menino, lutando a vida inteira dele. Para mim ele é o maior exemplo de vontade de viver e luta. Ele tem autismo e atraso cognitivo. Tem asma, faz uso de bombinha diário de manhã e à noite, pois quando dá UTI ele teve muitos problemas pulmonares. Foram 4 meses com uma água no pulmão que não melhorava. O pulmão dele sempre foi frágil. Esteve de novo em abril do ano passado na UTI . Dessa vez, pulmão, sempre ele, uma bactéria no pulmão e mais uma luta. A vida do Charles serve de exemplo para aqueles que acham que milagres não existem. Serve de motivação para que você nunca desista do seu sonhos.  #autismo #autista #tea #inclusao #motivacional #superacao #medicina #foryou #pravoce

Stimming is self-stimulating behaviors that involve repetitive movements or sounds. It commonly refers to behaviors, such as flapping one's arms or rocking back and forth, that are often seen in people diagnosed with autism. You don't have to be autistic to "stim." For example, tapping your foot when you're nervous could be an example of stimming. Stimming does look different, though, when it's an autism trait. Behaviors like finger flicking and twirling can become very excessive and obsessive in an autistic person. #signsofautismintoddlers  #autistictraits #toddlertiktok #toddlersoftiktok #asdstimming #stimmingpositivity #justkeepstimming #tics #toddlerlove #commonautistictraits #earlysignsofautism #handflapping #excessiveblinking #rockingbackandforth #headshaking #clothingsensitivity #handposturing #sensorystimming #happyville #babyshark

What are Gestalt phrases?  A gestalt is an intonation rich long or short phrase that to the gestalt language processor, conveys a very specific meaning. Most gestalt phrases are emotion based and most of the time do not seem to relate to the situation at hand. They are all used to process, communicate a need, or express emotions when other forms of communication are challenging. They can also be self-soothing or self-stimulation behavior, providing comfort or familiarity in stressful or overwhelming situations. If you’d like to learn more about how we incorporate these behaviors into speech therapy sessions to affirm and teach language skills, follow me on Instagram, TikTok and YouTube @support_the_spectrum #autism #autismspectrumdisorder #ASD #autismawareness #autismacceptance #educationalpurposes #autismspectrum #neurodiversity #autismcommunity #learnontiktok #teachersoftiktok #teacher #speechpathology #autismsupport #education #teacherlife #autismadvocacy #gestaltlanguageprocessing #GLP #languageacquisition #gestaltlanguageprocessor #autismoftiktok #neurodiversityaffirming #neurodiversityaffirmingpractices #gestaltlanguageprocessorslp #therapytiktok #therapytok #therapy #echolalia #scripting #immediateecholalia #delayedecholalia #skit #supportthespectrum

Headphones can help create a more controlled auditory environment by blocking out or muffling noises that may trigger sensory overload. Whether or not headphones are beneficial depends on each person's individual sensory preferences and needs! Here are ways to help your child keep them on: -Set an example: Wear headphones yourself or have siblings model wearing them.  -Try a toy: Let a favorite toy wear headphones for a short time.  -Choose the right headphones: Consider noise-canceling headphones or headphones with ear cushions made of a different material. Some recommend kid-sized headphones that come in different colors. -Offer alternatives: If headphones aren’t working, try noise-reduction earmuffs, which are worn over the ears.  - Be consistent  #noisecancellingheadphones #asd #autism #autismawareness #adhd #autismacceptance #specialneeds #autistic #autismmom #autismfamily #autismsigns #signsofautism #autismmum #autismfamily #autismspectrumdisorder #autismspectrum #autismsupport #autismlife #autismparents #sensoryprocessingdisorder #neurodiversity #actuallyautistic #disability #autismcommunity #autismadvocate #toddersoftiktok #fyp #foryou #viral #kidsoftiktok

I used to think that a self diagnosis was not okay. Why? Because I thought it was kinda a slap in the face to those who were diagnosed autistic. But oh how my thought process has changed!!! I recently went for an autism diagnosis after hours and hours of researching on the internet about autism and how it presents in women. The outcome? Well the evaluator told me that I had all the autistic traits in all areas with sensory scoring the highest but BECAUSE my functioning levels are fine and I’m living life just fine (not handicap) 🥴, I did not meet the criteria for the autism diagnosis. But that I should identify as autistic and was given autism support groups to join. So now if you’d ask me if I support a self diagnosis I would say 100% not just because of situations like mine but for other reasons like money (it’s super expensive), not everyone has the resources, grown adults who have lived their entire lives undiagnosed and now just know, and honestly so many other reason that don’t need to be listed or even explained. Because you don’t need to explain anything to anyone. Your feelings are valid! What you go through is valid!!! 💖 #autisminwomen #actuallyautistic  #autismfamily #autismcommunity #neurodivergentcommunity #neurodivergent #selfdiagnosis

A Message to the Autism Community: 🗣️ Just because a person cannot lead a conversation does NOT mean that they shouldn’t be included in it. Why is that a problem? ❌ ➡️ Because the most pressing issues I face as a “level 1” autistic person will be a lot different from the issues Colby, and people like him are facing. “I love bed rotting” “my room is a bit messy, it’s such a depression room rn!”  None of this is fun or quirky. It’s debilitating. And I know my room is disgusting and unhygienic but this is the reality of what depression can do to some people. i’m not lazy and the mess does bother me greatly, but I physically am not able to do anything about it.  This is hard for me to post because i’m so embarrassed about the state of my room and don’t want anyone to see it and judge me. Most of my closest friends have never even seen my room, because this is the state it’s in 98% of the time. But i want to be open and vulnerable on here to show people it’s nothing to be ashamed about. Depression is an extremely painful sickness and even surviving through the day is a great battle, so if your room also looks like this or if you’re beating yourself up for having a messy room, know that i’m proud of you and you are doing the very best you can !  I’m also seeing allot of people refer to there room as a ‘depression’ room as a way of using the word depression as an adjective. Depression is not an adjective. It’s an incredible difficult illness that many people d!€ from. It should not be used as a replacement for the word ‘messy’. If a few of your clothes are on your chair instead of in your closet or if you forgot to put away a cup; that’s something very different from a ‘depression room’. People who suffer from depression find even getting up to use the toilet too much sometimes; our room reflects how our depression manifests itself (and it’s not pretty)  I for example how molding food in my room, countless empty bottles and plates, used bandages that have never been thrown away and even mice and other insects. I cannot see my floor. I’m constantly breaking my neck trying to get to my bed or out of my room. I’ve broken countless things by accidently having stepped on them. I have no idea where most of my clothes are or if any of it is even clean. I’ve lost many important things because of the state of my room. I’m constantly late (which i am known for among my friends) but what they don’t know is it’s because i can’t find anything, which in turn stresses me out till the point of a panic attack, but i’m always too embarrassed to tell them that.  One thing that also upsets me is how much ‘bed rotting’ has become a trend. Taking a nap or laying in a little longer, is not ‘rotting’, that’s just resting. There have been a few times in my life where is spent weeks in my bed, and the only time I ever got up was to go to the toilet (and usually only after many hours of trying to ignore the fact that i have to pee because I didn’t want get up). One of the worst depressions in my life I spent 3 whole months in bed. And the entire time i did this, my bed clothes where not changed once. My pillow soaked up all the dirt of my unwashed hair and in turn made my skin horrible. In those 3 months i also gained an immense amount of weight because i was not moving. Other times I didn’t eat at all because I was too sucked into my ‘bed rotting’ i couldn’t even be bothered to make food.  None of this should be a ‘trend’, it’s not in anyway quirky or funny. It’s life altering and so incredibly difficult to go through and live with.  If you are also going through this right now, I want you to know i hear you and see you and to never be ashamed of the things you’ve done because of your depression, that is how you survived and i’m proud of you, and hope things start getting better for you soon <3   #mentalhealthmatters #venttok #depression #depressionroom #bedrotting #depressiveepisode #bedrottingcore #depressionroomcheck #depressionawareness

Part 4: There are many different “categories” of sensory processing disorder. Sometimes you may notice your child is falling into the exact opposite of all of the things i listed here. These are sensory seeking characteristics and it is a way for your child to meet their sensory system’s needs.  **DISCLAIMER, I do not make medical diagnoses. Do you also bite your nails when you’re stressed or anxious?  Using something chewlery instead is a smart idea, but changing routine and the way the body reacts can sometimes  be tricky, especially if you’re neurodivergent. Nail picking or chewing is definitely one of my bad stims (self regulating or stimulating behaviors), it’s very annoying autonomous and can hurt a lot at times.  Everyone stims and can have these habits or coping mechanisms, neurodivergent or not. and it’s about finding ways to do it in a way that doesn’t hurt or redirecting it into something that would be helpful and not hurtful.  #autismawareness #autistic #sensoryprocessingdisorder #spd #stimming #nailbiting #anxiety #anxious #stress #adhd #autistictiktok #disabled #autisme #autist #angst

Drawing mental disorders: Sensory processing disorder (SPD) is a condition that affects how your brain processes sensory information. Many individuals on the #autism spectrum exhibit a cognitive style often referred to as "thinking in pictures," where visual mental representations and processes are utilized more frequently than verbal ones. Studies have supported this visual bias, and this reliance on pictorial thinking is believed to explain many characteristic behaviors of autism, such as enhanced perceptual functioning and specific cognitive strengths in visual tasks. A Message to the Autism Community: 🗣️ Just because a person cannot lead a conversation does NOT mean that they shouldn’t be included in it. Why is that a problem? ❌ ➡️ Because the most pressing issues I face as a “level 1” autistic person will be a lot different from the issues Colby, and people like him are facing. Hear me out..  I’m not suggesting the company’s products are bad, but I do believe these specific items might not be suitable for your child. 👇🏻 **Folate**: Research shows 98% of children with autism are undermethylators and intolerant to folate, which can damage cells and worsen behavioral symptoms over time. When synthetic folate overwhelms the system, it can inhibit the transport and uptake of natural folate into the cells. This disrupts normal cellular processes, particularly in the nucleus where DNA synthesis and repair occur. The lack of sufficient active folate in the nucleus can lead to improper DNA methylation and repair, potentially damaging the cells at a genetic level. There is a difference between supplemental folate and natural folate. **Citric Acid**: - **Effects on ADHD and Autism**:  - **Sensitivities**: Some children may have sensitivities to citric acid, causing gastrointestinal discomfort and exacerbating behavioral symptoms. **Natural Flavors**: - **Effects on ADHD and Autism**:  - **Ingredient Ambiguity**: “Natural flavors” can include various substances, making it hard to identify specific triggers. Some may affect neurotransmitter activity and exacerbate hyperactivity or irritability. **Pure Body**: Detoxing alone won’t solve everything. Zeolites are not the safest or most effective method, as they can cause gastrointestinal discomfort, dehydration, and nutrient absorption issues, worsening symptoms. Also can be very taxing on the kidneys.  **Probiotics**: Children with autism may be sensitive to probiotics and histamine, disrupting gut balance and causing gastrointestinal discomfort and behavioral changes. Histamine intolerance can lead to headaches, digestive issues, and irritability. Feeling more confused than ever? Comment “ACADEMY” ⭐️⭐️ ✅to learn about my Healing With Hope Academy. Asperger syndrome was a term used to describe a developmental disorder on the autism spectrum characterised by significant difficulties in social interaction and nonverbal communication, alongside restricted and repetitive patterns of behavior and interests. Individuals with Asperger syndrome typically had average to above-average intelligence and did not exhibit a delay in language development.  People with Asperger syndrome were said to have focused interests, sometimes to an intense degree, and may have excelled in specific fields or hobbies.  In 2013, the DSM-5 reclassified Asperger syndrome under the broader category of Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD), which now encompasses various conditions previously diagnosed separately. There is also significant controversy surrounding Hans Asperger, after whom the condition was named. #asperger #autism #asd #mentalhealth #psychiatry #psychiatrist

#CapCut Mon petit frère Enzo est autiste sévère avec déficience intellectuelle associée. Il a appris à gérer les stimulations extérieures avec l'ABA: le bruit, la lumière et maintenant on peut l'emmener presque partout et il adore!!! Le handicap invisible correctement pris en charge permet une réelle inclusion dans la société et mon frère en est bien la preuve. Bon… aujourd’hui un grogne grogne sauvage apparaît. La difficulté est que comme avec un enfant en bas âge on fini par s’habituer à sa manière d’articuler, on le comprend mieux lui et ce qu’il veut ou ce qui lui fait plaisir. Enzo s’engouffre rapidement dans cette brèche et fait de moins en moins d’effort pour parler et articuler. Nous restons ferme car nous ne voulons pas qu’il régresse. Il nous fait rire, il en faut peu pour être heureux. Si tu veux en apprendre plus sur l'autisme ou la joie de vivre abonne toi à nos différents réseaux sociaux:  @Enzoetcharlotte  ! #handicapinvisible #autismesevere #autisteadulte #petitfrereautiste #tsa #deficienceintellectuelle #autism

#CapCut Enzo c’est mon petit frère, il est autiste sévère avec déficience intellectuelle associée et il a appris à gérer les stimulations extérieures avec l'ABA: le bruit, la lumière et maintenant on peut l'emmener presque partout et il adore!!! Le handicap invisible correctement pris en charge permet une réelle inclusion dans la société et mon frère en est bien la preuve. On a l’habitude de lui apprendre de nouveaux mots et de nouvelles expressions. On ne peut pas lui donner une définition claire d’un mot, ça n’a aucun sens pour Enzo. Il faut pratiquer avec lui et le faire s’en servir dans le bon contexte. Certains mots l’amuse plus que d’autre et il peut les utiliser de manière répétée à tout va. Petit à petit en pratiquant il apprend à s’en servir et à étoffer son lexique et sa réparti. Les apprentissages mis en place depuis son enfance, la patience et le travail d’Enzo permettent cette inclusion. Il nous a appris qu'il en faut peu pour être heureux. The most common myth about dyslexia is that we’re seeing the words incorrectly. That’s actually not true. The reason words or sounds get jumbled up is because we’re using the wrong part of our brain to process the written words. So, it has nothing to do with our eyes and everything to do with our brains. Our brains are wired differently! What are Gestalt phrases?  A gestalt is an intonation rich long or short phrase that to the gestalt language processor, conveys a very specific meaning. Most gestalt phrases are emotion based and most of the time do not seem to relate to the situation at hand. They are all used to process, communicate a need, or express emotions when other forms of communication are challenging. They can also be self-soothing or self-stimulation behavior, providing comfort or familiarity in stressful or overwhelming situations. Headphones can help create a more controlled auditory environment by blocking out or muffling noises that may trigger sensory overload. Whether or not headphones are beneficial depends on each person's individual sensory preferences and needs! Here are ways to help your child keep them on: -Set an example: Wear headphones yourself or have siblings model wearing them.  -Try a toy: Let a favorite toy wear headphones for a short time.  -Choose the right headphones: Consider noise-canceling headphones or headphones with ear cushions made of a different material. Some recommend kid-sized headphones that come in different colors. -Offer alternatives: If headphones aren’t working, try noise-reduction earmuffs, which are worn over the ears.  - Be consistent  #noisecancellingheadphones #asd #autism #autismawareness #adhd #autismacceptance #specialneeds #autistic #autismmom #autismfamily #autismsigns #signsofautism #autismmum #autismfamily #autismspectrumdisorder #autismspectrum #autismsupport #autismlife #autismparents #sensoryprocessingdisorder #neurodiversity #actuallyautistic #disability #autismcommunity #autismadvocate #toddersoftiktok #fyp #foryou #viral #kidsoftiktok

A Message to the Autism Community: 🗣️ Just because a person cannot lead a conversation does NOT mean that they shouldn’t be included in it.  Too often, language-abled people like me dominate advocacy spaces.  Why is that a problem? ❌ ➡️ Because the most pressing issues I face as a “level 1” autistic person will be a lot different from the issues Colby, and people like him are facing.  Folks with “level 3” or “profound autism” deserve to be highlighted in advocacy efforts, even if they’re not able to lead them. 💕 #autism #autistic #autismawareness #autisticadult #profoundautism #actuallyautistic

🌟 Parents of Autistic Children, Listen Up! 🌟 After 20 years in the autism world, here’s my biggest piece of advice: Understanding Your Child’s Behavior is Key! 🔑 Every behavior your child shows – good, bad, problem-solving – serves a purpose. It’s shaped by the world around them. 🌍 Here's What You Need to Do: 1️⃣ Learn what your child is trying to communicate 🗣️ 2️⃣ Teach them more effective communication strategies 📖 3️⃣ Watch problem behaviors go away because they have better tools 🔧 Why is this Important? 💖 Honors your child’s unique experience 🎯 Respects their inherent desires 🫶 Allows them to feel understood The Result? ✨ A happier child and a happier you! ✨ Join me in enhancing your child’s life experience and yours too! Life lately has been overwhelming in a way I’ve never experienced before. Part of it has to do with what people seem to expect of us without having any idea what goes into each day or what we have to consider when we do things outside of our daily routine. What you can do to support them: The key is to support or ask for help in a way that doesn't feel overwhelming or exhausting for them. Here are some examples: - I was thinking of watching a new movie tonight, and I'd love your company. Do you mind if I come over with snacks? We can just relax and enjoy the it together. - I'm trying out different tea blends and could really use your help to choose the best one. Want to join me for a tea tasting session? - There’s a new cafe that opened up nearby, and I heard they have great coffee. Want to check it out with me? My treat! - It's a great evening for a drive. How about we just cruise around for a bit while listening to some good music? I can pick you up in an hour! Keep in mind that, sometimes, they might not be up to hosting at their place if they think it’s untidy, and going out might seem overwhelming if it requires a lot of preparation or too much energy. So opt for activities that are simple and enjoyable — things that won't drain their energy but will genuinely make them feel included and valued. This way, you offer support without adding pressure. Hear me out..  I’m not suggesting the company’s products are bad, but I do believe these specific items might not be suitable for your child. 👇🏻 **Folate**: Research shows 98% of children with autism are undermethylators and intolerant to folate, which can damage cells and worsen behavioral symptoms over time. When synthetic folate overwhelms the system, it can inhibit the transport and uptake of natural folate into the cells. This disrupts normal cellular processes, particularly in the nucleus where DNA synthesis and repair occur. The lack of sufficient active folate in the nucleus can lead to improper DNA methylation and repair, potentially damaging the cells at a genetic level. There is a difference between supplemental folate and natural folate. **Citric Acid**: - **Effects on ADHD and Autism**:  - **Sensitivities**: Some children may have sensitivities to citric acid, causing gastrointestinal discomfort and exacerbating behavioral symptoms. **Natural Flavors**: - **Effects on ADHD and Autism**:  - **Ingredient Ambiguity**: “Natural flavors” can include various substances, making it hard to identify specific triggers. Some may affect neurotransmitter activity and exacerbate hyperactivity or irritability. **Pure Body**: Detoxing alone won’t solve everything. Zeolites are not the safest or most effective method, as they can cause gastrointestinal discomfort, dehydration, and nutrient absorption issues, worsening symptoms. Also can be very taxing on the kidneys.  **Probiotics**: Children with autism may be sensitive to probiotics and histamine, disrupting gut balance and causing gastrointestinal discomfort and behavioral changes. Histamine intolerance can lead to headaches, digestive issues, and irritability. Feeling more confused than ever? Comment “ACADEMY” ⭐️⭐️ ✅to learn about my Healing With Hope Academy. After leading my son to overcome his symptoms and achieve success, I developed this program. While I was never bothered social questions as an autistic kid myself…SO MANY of my clients are.  They just don’t find connection that way. 🤷🏼‍♀️ 📝 Through my 9 years of clinical experience supporting kids on the autism spectrum…here’s some things to try instead: ▪️ Use open body language to show you’re available ▪️Narrate/describe their actions ▪️Play with similar objects nearby  ▪️Follow the child’s lead ▪️Be responsive to their movements, sounds, and words ▪️Make STATEMENTS about what you see/hear/feel/think  #autistic #autism #aba #autismacceptance #autismawareness #therapist #neruodivergent #pda #autismmom #therapy

Caption: Enchentes na Europa - A tempestade Boris já deixou pelo menos 17 mortos em cinco países da Europa Central e Oriental, segundo balanço divulgado nesta segunda-feira (16) pela agência de notícias Reuters. Ventos e chuvas fortes atingem a Áustria, a República Tcheca, a Hungria, a Romênia e a Eslováquia desde o final da semana passada, causando graves inundações e danos materiais ainda difíceis de quantificar. Segundo informações da imprensa local, são as piores enchentes já enfrentadas na região em quase 30 anos. Além das sete mortes registradas na Romênia, a Áustria anunciou duas novas mortes: de dois homens com 70 e 80 anos, depois da de um bombeiro no dia anterior. Na República Tcheca, a polícia confirmou à rádio estatal a morte de uma pessoa que se afogou, além de sete desaparecidos. A polícia polonesa relatou quatro vítimas e o primeiro-ministro Donald Tusk anunciou a ajuda imediata de 260 milhões de dólares, o equivalente a R$ 1,44 bilhão. Saiba mais no #g1. #enchentes #europa

Hari pertama pembukaan Ibu Kota Nusantara (IKN) untuk masyarakat umum berlangsung aman, lancar, dan tertib, Senin (16/9/2024). Masyarakat demikian antusias menyambut pembukaan hari perdana ini, seiring dengan libur Maulid Nabi Besar Muhammad SAW. Otorita IKN (OIKN) mencatat, kuota 300 tiket yang dibuka hari perdana melalui aplikasi iKnow ini, langsung habis kurang dari satu jam. Sementara masyarakat yang kehabisan tiket terus berdatangan. Selain masyarakat umum dari seluruh Indonesia seperti Balikpapan, Samarinda, Banjarmasin, dan Jakarta, ada juga sepasang turis asal Jerman. Simak selengkapnya dalam video berikut! We’ve been fed this idea that to “get it right” we need to build perfect routines, stick to them religiously, and somehow transform our lives overnight. Especially as neurodivergent women, we’re told to juggle everything seamlessly, as if that’s even possible.  But let’s be honest for a moment—it’s not. The more we push ourselves to make these huge, life-altering changes, the quicker we fall into overwhelm. And that’s not sustainable. The truth is you don’t need to overhaul your entire life to feel in control or at peace. ✨ One small shift. ✨ That’s all it takes.  Maybe it’s five minutes of quiet in the morning or simply cutting out one distraction before bed. It may feel insignificant, but those little actions compound.  Suddenly, you’re not overwhelmed. You’re actually starting to feel more you. Once that one habit sticks, you add another. And another. No burnout, no pressure to be perfect—just a system that works with your brain, not against it.  So, let’s stop trying to do it all at once, You’re setting yourself up for failure. Instead, start with one small change and let it build into something beautiful.  If you want support and some guidance, I’ve got a free habit-stacking workbook to help you along the way. Audrey is nonverbal and has autism. She becomes very sensitive when people don’t understand her. During her time at Rainbow Centre, she was taught to use a communication book to express herself. Through the book, she shows us what she wants or dislikes. In the video, you can hear her expressing discomfort verbally, which is why I asked her to be patient. Warning spots on your skin. ⚠️🕵🏻‍♂️ If you have a spot like this, see your dermatologist.❣️ Skin cancer comes in several different forms: It may often look like a pink, scaly, rough patch or bump, an irregularly pigmented dark spot, or a non healing wound… Sometimes it can be even be confused as other skin conditions like eczema or psoriasis…! Protect your skin from the sun, and see a derm if ever you see a suspicious lesion on your skin 🙏🏼 ••• Taches d'avertissement sur votre peau. ⚠️🕵🏻‍♂️ Si vous avez une tache comme celle-ci, consultez votre dermatologue. ❣️ Le cancer de la peau se présente sous plusieurs formes différentes : il peut souvent ressembler à une plaque ou une bosse rose, écailleuse et rugueuse, une tache sombre irrégulièrement pigmentée ou une plaie qui ne guérit pas... Parfois, il peut même être confondu avec d'autres affections cutanées comme l'eczéma ou le psoriasis...! Protégez votre peau du soleil et consultez un dermatologue si jamais vous voyez une lésion suspecte sur votre peau 🙏🏼 *Photos posted with patients’ consent // Photos publiées avec le consentement des patient(e)s.* #melanoma #melanomaawareness #melanomaawarenessmonth #skincancer #dermatology #dermatologist #sunscreenwins #sunscreen #sunprotection #protectyourskin #warningspot #basalcellcarcinoma #skincancerawareness #greenscreen

🌎 The world puts autistic people into 2 boxes; those viewed as “different” and those viewed as “disordered”.  Let me be perfectly clear in that I do NOT believe these unofficial distinctions are useful, and they’re certainly not correct. ❌ That said…I DO think it would be helpful to incorporate the distinction “profound autism” when appropriate. ✅  The folks who fit into this category are both the MOST vulnerable, and the LEAST represented. الصعوبات في التعرف على الوجوه عند التوحديين 1. ما هي الصعوبة في التعرف على الوجوه؟ الصعوبة في التعرف على الوجوه، والمعروفة علميًا بـ **عمى الوجوه (Prosopagnosia)**، هي حالة يعاني فيها الشخص من صعوبة في تمييز الوجوه وتذكرها. هذه الصعوبة قد تكون شائعة بشكل أكبر لدى التوحديين. 2. كيف تؤثر هذه الصعوبة على التوحديين؟ الأشخاص الذين يعانون من هذه الصعوبة قد يجدون صعوبة في التعرف على الأشخاص حتى بعد مقابلتهم عدة مرات. قد لا يتمكنون من تمييز بين وجوه أصدقائهم، زملائهم في المدرسة أو العمل، وحتى أفراد أسرهم، إلا إذا كان هناك شيء آخر يميزهم مثل تسريحة شعر فريدة أو نوع معين من الملابس. 3. لماذا يحدث هذا؟ التعرف على الوجوه يتطلب معالجة بصرية معقدة تشمل أجزاء محددة من الدماغ، مثل الفص الصدغي. في حالة التوحديين، قد يكون هناك اختلاف في طريقة عمل هذه الأجزاء من الدماغ، مما يؤدي إلى صعوبات في معالجة الوجوه والتعرف عليها. هذا لا يعني أن الشخص غير مهتم بالآخرين أو غير قادر على بناء علاقات اجتماعية، بل يعني أن دماغه يعالج المعلومات بشكل مختلف. 4. كيف يمكننا تقديم الدعم؟ - استخدام تلميحات إضافية: يمكنك تقديم تلميحات بصرية أو لفظية لمساعدة الشخص في التعرف على الآخرين، مثل تقديم الاسم مع وصف بسيط عن الشخص. - تفهم التحديات: تفهم أن الشخص قد يواجه صعوبة في تمييز الأشخاص لا يعني قلة الاهتمام، بل هو تحدٍ إدراكي يحتاج إلى دعم وتفهم. - الابتعاد عن الافتراضات: من المهم عدم افتراض أن الشخص غير اجتماعي أو غير مهتم بناءً على هذه الصعوبة. بدلاً من ذلك، حاول تسهيل التواصل باستخدام وسائل أخرى. 5. لماذا من المهم الوعي بهذه الصعوبة؟ الوعي بهذه الصعوبة يمكن أن يساهم في خلق بيئة أكثر دعمًا وتفهمًا للتوحديين. يمكن أن يقلل من سوء الفهم ويعزز من قدرتهم على التفاعل الاجتماعي في مجتمع يفهم احتياجاتهم بشكل أفضل.  الخلاصة الصعوبة في التعرف على الوجوه هي جانب مهم يجب فهمه عند التعامل مع التوحديين. من خلال الوعي والدعم المناسب، يمكننا مساعدتهم على التغلب على هذا التحدي وتحقيق تواصل اجتماعي أكثر فعالية. إذا أول مره تشوف حسابي  معاك غدير السليماني  أم لطفل توحدي  اخصائية ABA  مشرف توحد QASPS باحثه ماجستير نطق ولغة إذا كان لديك أي استفسار فلا تتردد في طرحه  #Autism #AutismAwareness #AutismSupport #AutismAcceptance #AutismFamily #AutismMom #AutismDad #AutismCommunity #AutismSpectrum #ActuallyAutistic #DifferentNotLess #AutismParenting #AutismJourney #التوحد #وعي_التوحد #دعم_التوحد #طفلي_التوحدي #أطفال_التوحد #التوحد_والتواصل #العالم_الازرق #نحن_معكم #التوحد_قوة_مختلفة #رحلة_غسان  #رحلة_غسان #CapCut

This video is aimed at beginner Golfers who might find themselves overwhelmed by the amount of information online regarding where to play the ball in your stance for each club. Golf is confusing when you first start out, so let's make one of the first fundamentals you should learn simple. I tell my new students just to remember 3 ball positions: Middle, an inch forward of Middle, and in line with your lead heel. The corresponding clubs match each position as outlined in the video. You will find success using these positions for these clubs not to mention it is one less thing in the game to make complex! As you progress you can move these around to create different flights and preferences, however this is a great starting point. #golf #golfer #golfing #golftips #golflesson #golftiktok #golftok #golflife #golfswing #golfball #golfvideo

AOA Aspirants! These are the 10 most basic things you need to know about the NUMS exam. 1. What is NUMS and NUMS MDCAT? NUMS stands for National University of Medical Sciences. It's a medical university that has 13 private colleges (Including 5 institutes of dentistry) under it and 1 Public college. In order to get admission in these colleges, Nums conducts its OWN SEPARATE ENTRY TEST called the Nums MDCAT. 2. How is it different from normal MDCAT?  Provincial MDCAT and Nums MDCAT are two separate tests. Nums test is only for Nums affiliated colleges, while provincial MDCAT is for the rest of the public and private colleges of Pakistan. 3. Is it important to pass provincial MDCAT for getting admission in Nums colleges? No, passing provincial mdcat is not compulsory. Only NUMS MDCAT will be counted. 4. What are the names of Nums affiliated colleges? Public: Army Medical College Rawalpindi Private: CMH Lahore Medical College CMH Kharian Medical College CMH Bahawalpur Institute of medical sciences CMH Multan Institute of medical sciences Fazaia medical college Islamabad Fazaia ruth Pfau medical college Karachi  Bahria medical and dental college Qeutta institute of medical sciences (QIMS)  Karachi Institute of Medical Sciences (KIMS)   Wah Medical College, Wah Cantt.  Foundation University Medical College Islamabad  Nust school of health sciences Hitech institute of Medical Sciences 5. What is the syllabus and paper pattern? The syllabus is comparatively easier and less as compared to provincial MDCAT. Syllabus is available on Nums official website. Paper pattern includes: 150 MCQs from Biology, Chem, Physics and English (2.5 hours) 100 MCQs Psychological portion (30 minutes) Note: Only 5% of this portion will be counted in your exam. As you know Mikko stims a lot. Sucking her thumb and hair twirling is her go to for comfort. Even before we knew what Autism stimming was, This was always her thing since she was 3 months old. She didn’t quite like the pacifier and only really found comfort in her hands.  Thumb sucking can cause major dental issues with how her mouth is forming as she grows and because she is nonverbal, I fear that it can also hinder how she learns to communicates. Although this may be working at the moment, we are actively working toward a more permanent solution. Stimming is something that will naturally change as she grows, we just want to make sure it does not turn into a different unhealthy habit. #asd #autism #autismawareness #adhd #autismacceptance #specialneeds #autistic #autismmom #autismfamily #aspergers #autismspectrumdisorder #autismspectrum #autismsupport #autismlife #autismparents #autismlove #sensoryprocessingdisorder #differentnotless #neurodiversity #autismspeaks #autismdad #actuallyautistic #disability #autismo #anxiety #mentalhealth #downsyndrome #autismcommunity #love #autismadvocate

As a neurodiverse person I actually get excited to learn about how the brain works, what processes are called, and what the brain is capable of.  When something that I do is established as normal/not normal (baseline vs deviation) I don’t feel offended. I’ve been aware that my brain is “different” my entire life and I think that just makes me unique. Like a super hero. I don’t need to be like everyone else. And anyone that perceives me as less than for being different or not the norm is the problem, not me. It’s not my job to erase my “deviations” for broad appeal. Just as “I don’t see color” erases the beauty of what makes racial and ethnic cultures unique. “Stop calling things not normal/autistic/different/diverse” can erase the beauty of have a brain that’s calibrated differently.  #kadyroxz #mentalhealth #neurodivergent #autismawareness

AWETISM DAD BACK FROM HAJ ——————————————————- Being the sole breadwinner of our family and having a child on the Autism spectrum, miraculously, Dad managed to perform Haj. It was a once in a lifetime experience. When he got the call from MUIS, I said “Go, I will handle the kids.” I thought #chefmuaz wouldn’t mind Dad’s absence.  He was his usual self…until the arrival date approached, I could finally see he was looking forward to it. Muaz went up to our big whiteboard calendar in the living room, pointed to the correct date and mentioned “Daddy Daddy.” Yes, Daddy’s coming back today! And here's how the reunion went between dad and son, after being just one day apart. 🤭 Thanks to our ability to work from home, we've been deeply involved in every stage of Michael's growth from the very beginning, and we haven't missed a single moment together. For me, regardless of the challenges, I've never felt the need or want for a day apart from Michael.  His constant gentle nature plays a big part in this, but I take great joy in being present and involved in his daily life, not missing a single precious moment or milestone — no matter how small or trivial it may seem. Ramping up all the love and goodness, particularly in his formative years, has been our top priority.  This means ensuring that we are fully present at every stage of his young life — and not physically nor emotionally ‘away’. Accessibility is one of the many struggles people living with a disability face. By the time we’ve started our workday, we’ve often faced so many challenges because of the environment around us.  @unilever is one company which appreciates how important it is to create an environment that ensures their people can bring their best selves to work. And they’re committing to some ambitious targets to make it happen - aiming to be the number one employer of choice for people living with disabilities, and making their sites around the world fully accessible by 2025.  I say this a lot, but we can’t have diversity and representation without inclusion. It’s all well and good to hire people with disabilities, but it’s the small changes that have the biggest impact when it comes to truly creating an environment where all people thrive.  #UniquelyUnilever #Unilever AD

Good morning 💙.  Someone asked if I do chores? Ahhh, yes, I do. Having autism doesn't mean that my hands/feet don't work 💙, yes, it is true that learning chores may be a bit challenging and may have to be repeated to me/us several times since we learn best through visuals and that's OK, a Lil patience goes a long way 👍🏾 😀.  Doing chores has definitely benefitted me, as I am still learning to master my independency and life skills on a whole.  So start practicing/training your loved ones with routines/chores. Trust me, it works!HELP ME, HELP YOU! It's all big wins in our world 🌎. Williams @safespacesuk bed Has been life changing for us, before we had this bed he was unsafe to be left alone overnight (he would eat his bed frame, window boards, plaster off the walls etc)  Now when he’s in bed we know he’s safe ❤️  he can’t head bang the walls as his bed is set back so he can’t harm himself!  Also when he wakes throughout the night we can sometimes leave him with his iPad which means we get more sleep (amazing) 🙌🏼 I think the bed just helps him feel more safe, we also have a camera in his bed so we can keep a eye on him at all times. HOW WE GOT THE BED : (it’s a long one, be prepared to fight too, it didn’t come easy, just a mumma who didn’t give up)  We had a different brand bed (was a specialist) before which William broke within 6 months, rocking on the roof 😂 so they knew he needed something more robust. I begged, and rang the nhs OT weekly till they agreed to help me.  We then had a design meeting with @safespacesuk and the ot to work out exactly what William needed, looking back now there’s definitely things I’d change, we have a single bed in Williams and I think a bed covering the whole floor space is a better idea!  Once everyone agreed to the design the bed was then made, and funded by the NHS.  I am forever thankful for this bed & William absolutely loves it!  Ps William wanted the Christmas bedding on 😂😂😂 #fyp #autism #nonspeaking #nonverbal #autism #autistic #asd #autismawareness #autisticcommunity #autismmemes #autismacceptance #love #safespace #safespacebed #specialistbed  #motherhood  #viral #trending

In the autism community, we often think of “masking” as a way to seamlessly blend in with the people around us.  Maybe I’m doing it wrong, but that’s NOT been my experience.  I put in all the effort to do it…and it produces virtually the same result as if I hadn’t tried at all. I suppose that effort isn’t the same as results. You can try really hard and still not be able to achieve something.  In my case, I struggle to achieve warmth. I FEEL warm toward people inside, but not matter what I do…I can’t seem to achieve expressing that warmth on the outside. #autistic #actuallyautistic #neurodivergent #autism #autisticadult #unmasking #autismawareness #mentalhealth

Being black and autistic basically means that we don’t get to be weird and blame it on autism. Being black and autistic means that at every moment I have to be on guard and I have to put on a mask and be aware that I’m putting on a mask and constantly tweaking it based on the environment that I’m in it constantly suppressing because I can’t blame my weirdness on autism. it means that my autism can cause me to be an outcast and in my community that’s a danger because if you’re an outcast to your own community in the whole world already sees you as a threat that means you’re all alone and in danger.   #Autism #autizzy #neurospicy #autizzyasf #blackandautistic #actuallyautistic #audhd #autizzyaf #neurodivergent #rosaliespeaks

AWETISM DAD BACK FROM HAJ ——————————————————- Being the sole breadwinner of our family and having a child on the Autism spectrum, miraculously, Dad managed to perform Haj. It was a once in a lifetime experience. When he got the call from MUIS, I said “Go, I will handle the kids.” I thought #chefmuaz wouldn’t mind Dad’s absence.  He was his usual self…until the arrival date approached, I could finally see he was looking forward to it. Muaz went up to our big whiteboard calendar in the living room, pointed to the correct date and mentioned “Daddy Daddy.” Yes, Daddy’s coming back today! A reunion that we will never forget ❤️ #autismlife —————— IG: @lydiawatimz @chefmuaz Books #aworthyrace @ahopeworthaving : Wardah Books / Kinokuniya at Takashimaya

Why Autism in Women Is Often Overlooked: Understanding the Differences in Diagnosis Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD) can be easier to diagnose in adults, but women often go undiagnosed or misdiagnosed due to differences in how autism presents. Here’s why: Men with autism tend to fit the more stereotypical patterns of ASD, making their diagnosis more straightforward. Their struggles with emotional literacy and special interests are often more obvious. Women, however, often have more subtle or hidden traits. They may appear to master emotional literacy better and their special interests may not stand out as much, leading to a missed diagnosis. Women on the spectrum tend to show more variation in their special interests, whereas men may gravitate toward specific industries or skill sets, making their autism more noticeable. Understanding these gender differences is crucial for improving the diagnosis and support of women with autism, who often face unique challenges in a world that doesn’t recognize their experiences as easily. Learn more about how autism presents differently in women and why these differences matter for proper diagnosis and support. #autisminwomen  #autismawareness  #Neurodivergent

الصعوبات في التعرف على الوجوه عند التوحديين 1. ما هي الصعوبة في التعرف على الوجوه؟ الصعوبة في التعرف على الوجوه، والمعروفة علميًا بـ **عمى الوجوه (Prosopagnosia)**، هي حالة يعاني فيها الشخص من صعوبة في تمييز الوجوه وتذكرها. هذه الصعوبة قد تكون شائعة بشكل أكبر لدى التوحديين. 2. كيف تؤثر هذه الصعوبة على التوحديين؟ الأشخاص الذين يعانون من هذه الصعوبة قد يجدون صعوبة في التعرف على الأشخاص حتى بعد مقابلتهم عدة مرات. قد لا يتمكنون من تمييز بين وجوه أصدقائهم، زملائهم في المدرسة أو العمل، وحتى أفراد أسرهم، إلا إذا كان هناك شيء آخر يميزهم مثل تسريحة شعر فريدة أو نوع معين من الملابس. 3. لماذا يحدث هذا؟ التعرف على الوجوه يتطلب معالجة بصرية معقدة تشمل أجزاء محددة من الدماغ، مثل الفص الصدغي. في حالة التوحديين، قد يكون هناك اختلاف في طريقة عمل هذه الأجزاء من الدماغ، مما يؤدي إلى صعوبات في معالجة الوجوه والتعرف عليها. هذا لا يعني أن الشخص غير مهتم بالآخرين أو غير قادر على بناء علاقات اجتماعية، بل يعني أن دماغه يعالج المعلومات بشكل مختلف. 4. كيف يمكننا تقديم الدعم؟ - استخدام تلميحات إضافية: يمكنك تقديم تلميحات بصرية أو لفظية لمساعدة الشخص في التعرف على الآخرين، مثل تقديم الاسم مع وصف بسيط عن الشخص. - تفهم التحديات: تفهم أن الشخص قد يواجه صعوبة في تمييز الأشخاص لا يعني قلة الاهتمام، بل هو تحدٍ إدراكي يحتاج إلى دعم وتفهم. - الابتعاد عن الافتراضات: من المهم عدم افتراض أن الشخص غير اجتماعي أو غير مهتم بناءً على هذه الصعوبة. بدلاً من ذلك، حاول تسهيل التواصل باستخدام وسائل أخرى. 5. لماذا من المهم الوعي بهذه الصعوبة؟ الوعي بهذه الصعوبة يمكن أن يساهم في خلق بيئة أكثر دعمًا وتفهمًا للتوحديين. يمكن أن يقلل من سوء الفهم ويعزز من قدرتهم على التفاعل الاجتماعي في مجتمع يفهم احتياجاتهم بشكل أفضل.  الخلاصة الصعوبة في التعرف على الوجوه هي جانب مهم يجب فهمه عند التعامل مع التوحديين. من خلال الوعي والدعم المناسب، يمكننا مساعدتهم على التغلب على هذا التحدي وتحقيق تواصل اجتماعي أكثر فعالية. إذا أول مره تشوف حسابي  معاك غدير السليماني  أم لطفل توحدي  اخصائية ABA  مشرف توحد QASPS باحثه ماجستير نطق ولغة إذا كان لديك أي استفسار فلا تتردد في طرحه  #Autism #AutismAwareness #AutismSupport #AutismAcceptance #AutismFamily #AutismMom #AutismDad #AutismCommunity #AutismSpectrum #ActuallyAutistic #DifferentNotLess #AutismParenting #AutismJourney #التوحد #وعي_التوحد #دعم_التوحد #طفلي_التوحدي #أطفال_التوحد #التوحد_والتواصل #العالم_الازرق #نحن_معكم #التوحد_قوة_مختلفة #رحلة_غسان  #رحلة_غسان #CapCut

Types of sensory input  We have 8 sensory systems, they all contribute to our daily functioning and engagement with the world. Some of these systems are more ‘known’ and others may be new for you.  1. Tactile 2. Visual 3. Auditory 4. Gustation 5. Olfactory 6. Proprioception 7. Vestibular 8. Interoception It’s the input we receive from these 8 systems constantly during our day that our brain is receiving and interpreting. Childhood Trauma: It’s Not Just About What Happened to Us, But What Happened Around Us When we talk about childhood trauma, we often think of the abuse or neglect that happened to us. But let’s get real—trauma isn’t always about what happened directly to us. It’s also about what happened around us. 🌪️ Growing up in a home filled with constant arguments and conflict can be just as damaging. Here’s why: 🔸 Emotional Instability: A home should be a safe haven, not a battlefield. Constant conflict leaves you in a perpetual state of anxiety. 😟 🔸 Modeling Dysfunctional Behavior: Kids absorb what they see. Witnessing shouting and aggression teaches them these behaviors are normal. This can mess up their ability to form healthy relationships later in life. 🔄 🔸 Attachment Issues: A conflict-ridden home disrupts the formation of secure attachments. Trust becomes a foreign concept, making relationships feel like ticking time bombs. 💔 🔸 Self-Esteem and Worth: Constant arguments can make a child feel like they’re the problem, leading to guilt and low self-worth. These feelings stick into adulthood. 🚶‍♂️ Healing from the Unseen Wounds: 1. Awareness: Admit the environment was traumatic. Understand its lasting impact. 🌱 2. Therapy/Coach and Support: Seek professional help to explore these feelings and develop healthier healing mechanisms. 🛋️ 3. Healthy Relationships: Surround yourself with supportive, understanding people. Positive relationships can help rebuild trust and security. 🤝 4. Self-Compassion: Acknowledge your trauma is valid, even if it wasn’t direct abuse. Practice self-compassion to rebuild your self-esteem and sense of worth. ❤️ Childhood trauma isn’t always about what was done to us; it’s also about what happened around us. Recognizing these impacts and taking steps toward healing can help break the cycle of dysfunction and build a more stable, fulfilling life. 💪✨ #ChildhoodTrauma #MentalHealth #HealingJourney #EmotionalHealth #SelfCompassion #HealthyRelationships #BreakTheCycle ----

Otizmin belirtilerinin günlük yaşamda kendini nasıl gösterebileceği hakkında çocukluğumda yaşadığım örneklerden bahsettim. Bu belirtilere sahip olmanız otizmli olduğunuz anlamına gelmez. Her birey farklıdır ve benzer davranışlar farklı nedenlerden kaynaklanabilir. Yüksek işlevli otizmli kişilerin (özellikle de kadınların) çocukluklarında gözden kaçan otizm belirtileri, otizmin kalıplaşmış görüntüsünden farklı olduğu için tanı konulmasında zorlanılmıştır. Bu kişiler sosyal etkileşimlerde zorluk yaşayabilirler ve genellikle yalnız oynamayı tercih edebilirler. Bu durum, çoğunlukla utangaçlık veya içe dönüklük olarak yorumlanabilir. Ayrıca belirli konulara aşırı ilgi gösterebilirler. Örneğin, bilimsel bir konuya yoğun ilgi gösterebilirler ve bu konularda detaylı bilgi sahibi olabilirler. Bu tür ilgi alanları normal çocuk merakı veya hobisi olarak görüldüğünden fark edilmeyebilir. Duyusal hassasiyetler de sıkça görülür. Gürültü, parlak ışıklar veya belirli dokulara karşı aşırı hassas olabilirler, ancak bu hassasiyetler çocukların mızmızlığı veya seçici olmaları olarak yorumlanabilir. Diğer çocukların davranışlarını taklit ederek sosyal etkileşimlerde normal görünmeye çalışabilirler, bu da uyum sağlama veya arkadaş edinme çabası olarak görülebilir. #otizim #otizimfarkındalıktır #asperger #asd #audhd #aspergersendromu #yetişkinlikteotizm #neurodivergent #kadınlardaotizm #autism

Screen time can have specific negative impacts on children with autism, including: 1. **Social Skills**: Excessive screen time may limit opportunities for social interaction, which is crucial for children with autism to develop and practice social skills. 2. **Sensory Overload**: Screen time can contribute to sensory overload for children with autism, as they may be more sensitive to visual and auditory stimuli. This overload can lead to increased anxiety and difficulty in processing information. 3. **Rigid Behaviors**: Extended screen time can reinforce rigid behaviors and repetitive interests, which are common characteristics of autism, potentially limiting exposure to new experiences and activities. 4. **Communication Development**: Excessive screen time may interfere with the development of communication skills, including verbal and nonverbal communication, which are already areas of challenge for many children with autism. 5. **Attention Difficulties**: Children with autism may have difficulties with attention and focus, and excessive screen time can exacerbate these issues, making it harder for them to engage in other activities and learn from their environment. My son’s transformation from nonverbal severe autism in diapers to being potty trained and conversational was achieved solely through natural methods. These included dietary adjustments, lifestyle changes, detoxification, removing screens, and more. After implementing natural solutions my nonverbal 4 year old son in just a few months began to develop functional language, and within a year, he was conversational and flourishing.  By the end of two years, he no longer exhibited the symptoms that previously classified him as autistic.  That’s why I developed the Ultimate eBook Starter Pack, which contains the strategies I utilized to assist my son in flourishing. It is what it is. We’re like the X-MEN in many ways. The fight must go on... Tidak semua orang akan menerima, apatah lagi memahami. Tidak setiap kejiranan akan menyambut kami, sama ada menyewa atau memiliki. Jauh lagi perjalanannya  untuk wujudkan satu masyarakat yang betul mengamalkan inklusiviti. Akan ada situasi atau benda yang tidak sesuai untuk orang seperti kami yang ada anak seperti Adam. Inilah kenyataannya. Kami ibarat X-MEN... The weather has been HOT where I am, so sometimes indoor interventions are necessary-  When working with pediatric clients I love the versatility of obstacle courses. There are SO MANY THINGS that can be targeted for skill development and SO MUCH FUN that is possible. My favorite part is encouraging children to help design their own parts of the obstacle course.  Here are some of my favorite home materials/ideas for how they may be used - but don’t let this list limit your creativity!!  -Crash pad (jumping/crashing/proprioceptive input) -Trampoline (jumping, strength, balance) -Cones (Bilateral coordination, planning, boundaries) -Dress up clothes (ADLs, motor skills, social participation)  -Balls (visual motor integration, strengthening) -Hula hoops (hopping, weight-shifting/balance, boundaries)  -Slide (climbing, risky play, spatial orientation)  -Bean bags (heavy work, hand-eye coordination)  -Tunnels (crawling, body awareness, sensory needs)  -Scooter board (laying in prone (on belly) WITH squigz using to pull, push = proprioceptive input, motor planning, strength) -Laundry Basket (throwing into, scooping out, carrying, heavy work)  -Wobble cushion (stepping stone, balance)  -Balance beam (balance, visual motor skills) -sit and spin (sensory needs, strengthening, vestibular input) #theearthyot #occupationaltherapy #obstaclecourse #pediatrics #sensory #play #childdevelopment #motorskills #gradstudent #challenge #momsoftiktok #staycool #letsplay

Happy disability pride month, shakers!!  Over the past few months I’ve made great strides in being more confident about my scars and I want to share how. My breakthrough happened when I started to challenge my intrusive thoughts surrounding what I notice FIRST about people I meet. It’s easy for your ego to recognize something negative about how someone looks so that you feel less alone in your own insecurities.  When this were to happen, I’d consciously challenge myself to ask why that even matters, why I’m noticing, and healing that part of myself that WANTS to notice those things about other people. It takes a lot to change the way society built you at a young age to protect yourself, but what’s worth it in the end is the connections you create with others and yourself while overcoming this hurdle.  Just a thought I wanted to share this disability pride month, and I urge you to try and think in a similar way if you notice yourself thinking these things, regardless if it’s towards an able bodied person or not!  Stay cute & kind ❤️ #disability #disabilitypride #disabilitytiktok #fyp

It’s Global Accessibility Awareness Day, so it seems like a fitting day to share what happened on my flight to Costa Rica last week. This is me, being carried down a flight of stairs in a broken aisle chair — no armrests, straps that wouldn’t tighten enough to keep my body in, and front wheels that were busted off.  You can see from my face how distraught and absolutely terrified I was. The individuals that were sent to help me disembark this plane likely had very little training on how to do so; they kept having to place the chair down from not having the correct grip, and they were holding the chair completely sideways (hence my dad trying his best to hold my head so it didn’t completely fall over).  We didn’t speak the same language so they continued along without understanding my repeated “no’s”. Never in my life have I felt so out of control and so disconnected from my body.  I was never informed that this would be how I would have to disembark the plane, and it never crossed my mind given that this airport DOES use jet bridges. In fact, all of the other planes around us were pulled up to them.  I love sharing my travels as a wheelchair user because I truly believe that there is so much in this world is accessible and I want to inspire people to experience that. But, this is one of those instances where traveling with a disability is, unfortunately, not so glamorous.  It’s 2024, disabled people deserve a more dignified and safe way to fly. #rightsonflights @Air Canada

Is it possible that writing in cursive is helpful for people (especially kids) who have dyslexia? Some educators believe that merging letters with a continuous flow helps people with dyslexia better hold onto their train of thought, increases their writing speed and efficiency, and boosts their confidence. While there is no cure for dyslexia (and this absolutely is NOT one), sometimes hacks and accommodations make things most neurotypicals find ordinary much more accessible to neurodivergent people. ##Dyslexia##cursive

As you know Mikko stims a lot. Sucking her thumb and hair twirling is her go to for comfort. Even before we knew what Autism stimming was, This was always her thing since she was 3 months old. She didn’t quite like the pacifier and only really found comfort in her hands.  Thumb sucking can cause major dental issues with how her mouth is forming as she grows and because she is nonverbal, I fear that it can also hinder how she learns to communicates. Although this may be working at the moment, we are actively working toward a more permanent solution. Stimming is something that will naturally change as she grows, we just want to make sure it does not turn into a different unhealthy habit. #asd #autism #autismawareness #adhd #autismacceptance #specialneeds #autistic #autismmom #autismfamily #aspergers #autismspectrumdisorder #autismspectrum #autismsupport #autismlife #autismparents #autismlove #sensoryprocessingdisorder #differentnotless #neurodiversity #autismspeaks #autismdad #actuallyautistic #disability #autismo #anxiety #mentalhealth #downsyndrome #autismcommunity #love #autismadvocate

Children with autism spectrum disorder (ASD) are more likely to have sleep issues than children who develop typically. Up to 80% of children with ASD may have sleep difficulties at some point in their childhood, and these problems can be chronic. Sleep issues can start around 30 months of age and include: *Insomnia *Bedtime settling issues *Sleep anxiety *Night waking *Poor sleep quality *Sleep-disordered breathing *Irregular sleeping and waking patterns *Sleeping less than expected for their age *Being awake for more than an hour during the night *Getting up and doing their favorite activity or making noise during the night #autism #autismawareness #autismacceptance #autistic #autistictiktok #autistictoddler #autistictok #autisticgirl #trending #trendingtiktok #trendingnow #sleep #sleepover #nonap #nap #napping #nosleep #nosleepgang #zippadeezip #sleepsack

Replying to @Cora_Naturally my top 15 autistic traits that i recognized in myself that caused me to seek a diagnosis: 1. Sensory “quirks” 2. Mentally rehearsing every conversation 3. Overthinking eye contact  4. The need to fidget/stim…. ALL the time  5. Hyper-fixations 6. Self educated 7. Info dumping about one subject 8. Social chameleon / high masking 9. Feel like an alien 10. Prefer to be at home 11. Struggle to maintain friendships  12. Sensory overwhelm 13. Social anxiety 14. Intense self imposed rules  15. Meltdowns/ shut downs NOTE: This is NOT a diagnostic tool. This is just my experience. However, if you experience a lot of these traits, it might be worth exploring, and researching to see if you might also be autistic! I highly recommend reading  Unmasking Autism by Devon Price, and checking out the RAADSR and CATQ tests on the embrace, autism site.  #autistic #actuallyautistic #audhd #emilieleyes #autisticadult #neurodivergent #mentalhealth #autismawareness

Talk to your kids about neurodiversity. Talk to your kids about acceptance- start these conversations young so that accepting people who are different from them becomes second nature.  My educator lens taught me a lot about the spectrum of abilities - it also showed me just how inconsiderate and outright mean some had it in them to be. Being a teacher showed me when we lump individuals together with labels without understanding their actual meaning, we don’t even try to see them for them. So be a person who tries. Childhood Trauma: It’s Not Just About What Happened to Us, But What Happened Around Us When we talk about childhood trauma, we often think of the abuse or neglect that happened to us. But let’s get real—trauma isn’t always about what happened directly to us. It’s also about what happened around us. 🌪️ Growing up in a home filled with constant arguments and conflict can be just as damaging. Here’s why: 🔸 Emotional Instability: A home should be a safe haven, not a battlefield. Constant conflict leaves you in a perpetual state of anxiety. 😟 🔸 Modeling Dysfunctional Behavior: Kids absorb what they see. Witnessing shouting and aggression teaches them these behaviors are normal. This can mess up their ability to form healthy relationships later in life. 🔄 🔸 Attachment Issues: A conflict-ridden home disrupts the formation of secure attachments. Trust becomes a foreign concept, making relationships feel like ticking time bombs. 💔 🔸 Self-Esteem and Worth: Constant arguments can make a child feel like they’re the problem, leading to guilt and low self-worth. These feelings stick into adulthood. 🚶‍♂️ Healing from the Unseen Wounds: 1. Awareness: Admit the environment was traumatic. Understand its lasting impact. 🌱 2. Therapy/Coach and Support: Seek professional help to explore these feelings and develop healthier healing mechanisms. 🛋️ 3. Healthy Relationships: Surround yourself with supportive, understanding people. Positive relationships can help rebuild trust and security. 🤝 4. Self-Compassion: Acknowledge your trauma is valid, even if it wasn’t direct abuse. Practice self-compassion to rebuild your self-esteem and sense of worth. ❤️ Childhood trauma isn’t always about what was done to us; it’s also about what happened around us. Recognizing these impacts and taking steps toward healing can help break the cycle of dysfunction and build a more stable, fulfilling life. 💪✨ #ChildhoodTrauma #MentalHealth #HealingJourney #EmotionalHealth #SelfCompassion #HealthyRelationships #BreakTheCycle ----

Good morning 💙.  As many of you know,  I didn't start speaking till I was about 6 years old, which is still an emotional topic for my mom. In today's post, I wanted to have a conversation with my mom about my "first words" and listen to her response. I know there are many parents going through this same emotion, and I understand that it's not easy, buttt look at me. My progress might be slow, but it sure is steady,faith, hope, community, and most importantly, family helped me and still is helping me each and every day! So stay encouraged, and know that your reward is on its way!  Remember, it's all BIG WINS IN OUR WORLD 🌎.  Have a great holiday! ⏬Rasgos neurodivergentes que no todo el mundo entiende: ⏬ 1 No toleran el contacto físico con cualquiera, es decir, sólo toleran el contacto físico con personas específicas de su elección, ya que tienen un procesamiento sensorial distinto a las personas normativas, lo que hace que lo perciban de forma más intensa e invasiva.  2 Hacen hiperfoco en temas muy concretos y necesitan saber todo sobre ese tema, aunque esto requiera días o semanas de estudio, porque su cerebro libera dopamina cuando entran en este estado de concentración máxima y sienten felicidad extrema cuando están en él.  3 Escuchan la misma canción o ven la misma película o serie una y otra vez y luego la abandonan de forma drástica, esto se produce porque les estimula sensorialmente, les ayuda a la autorregulación y son capaces de analizarlas a un nivel cada vez más profundo, pero una vez que ya no pueden extraer más información, desaparece el interés por ellas.  4 Se sobreestimulan muy rápido con luces, sonidos o multitudes porque son capaces de captar más estímulos que las personas normativas y además hacen un procesamiento de la información más profundo.  Y tú, ¿Cuántos de estos rasgos tienes? #aacc #altascapacidades #tdah #tda #estudiar #dislexia #concentracion #neurodiversidad #neurodivergente #mindfulnes #psiquiatra #memoria #recordar #comoestudiar #psicologiapositiva #neurodivergencia #atencion #distraccion #soñar #soñardespierto

It’s Better Together! ADHD Coworking! A lot of neurodiverse folks find that coworking (or body doubling), coming together to do our separate work together, improves focus and productivity tremendously. Being socially motivated to show up, in order to ensure the other people can get *their* stuff done, supports us to get ours done, too. Members of The ADHD Guild support one another with their goals, and in coworking. Video Source: YT video on "Why New Tiers for The ADHD Guild? Kev is very linear in his thinking and often struggles with adapting his thought process to situations that occurs differently to the way he has planned them. In the scenario in this video he had a budget of £10 for a box of choclates for his teacher and Kev never wants to go over his set budget.  In the past simple situations like this can totally throw him off and even cause a meltown. He’s so much better now at listening to, acknowleding and sometimes accepting other perspectives with a gentle approach and careful explanation. We truly have come a long and I’ve found that tailoring my parenting meeting his needs has been the most beneficial. I’ve had a lot of learning and unlearning to do as a parent and when i see little progress like it makes it all worth it ❤️ #autisticteen #autismawareness #autismacceptance #autismdaily #neurodivergent #neurodiversity #autismparenting #africanautismmom #fyp

As a mom of a neurodiverse child, this news hits hard. I can’t stop thinking about Mason’s family, the unimaginable pain they must be feeling right now, and how they’ll have to navigate a world without their son.  When we send our children to school, we do so trusting that they’ll come back to us safe. And for those of us with autistic children, the fear cuts deep. Our kids, who may not understand danger the way others do, are especially vulnerable in these situations.  This is a moment for all of us—parents, educators, and communities—to come together and demand change. We need to ensure that every child, especially those with special needs, are protected and valued in our society. Mason’s life mattered. Autistic lives matter. #autisticlivesmatter #autismfamily #momsoftiktok #blackkidsmatter  #pray

Autism and adaptation to changes.  ♥♥♥♥🙂👍👍👍 If we want a child with ASD to cope with everyday life and be independent in adulthood, we should create such a space that allows them to experience as much as possible. Routine is the enemy… it is routine, limitation of experience, too many patterns that make it difficult to adapt to changes. Of course - an autistic person should feel safe, and routine gives him that feeling. However, life is not comfortable, you actually have to leave your comfort zone all the time. Give your child an adventure, explore ... Do not buy expensive clothes, toys, they do not teach anything. Getting to know the world, culture and customs plus nature. It makes a child... It teaches adaptation, understanding the world and kindness. What is the Intense World Theory⁉️ The theory states that autism involves hyper-capabilities such as: ✅ Hyper-perception ✅ Hyper-attention ✅ Hyper-memory ✅ Hyper-emotions The theory also proposes that the intense experiences can become overwhelming or even painful for individuals with autism, potentially leading to withdrawal and avoidance behaviours.  We’re still learning so much about autism with continued research bringing new theories, new revelations and sometimes, new questions. The Intense World Theory definitely resonates with me and my experiences parenting my beautiful neurodivergent boys. I think it’s so important to be open be openminded. Expose yourself to these discussions and of course, make your own decisions.  ##intenseworldtheory##autismstudy#autismexplained

The clapping and the smiles as he was getting onto the plane 😭😭 I’ve been so anxious all week, knowing this was about to happen. When I woke up to the video of him getting onto the plane it felt like a weight had been taken off my chest. Going on holiday isn’t something I’ve thought was a possibility for us. The risk of how Tommy would cope with the airport, the crowds, the waiting. What if there was a delay? Then there’s the flight itself, staying seated for so long, not being able to jump, kick, run, and be free like he usually is. Tommy also loves routine. He swaps back and forth between me and his mum every couple of days, and he gets extremely anxious if there’s any changes to that. But, he’s been told he’s going away for 7 days. He has a visual schedule, and now I keep my fingers crossed that he’s just as happy for the rest of the week.  I should have been a little more confident. This year we’ve been to the beach, a theme park, on a train and to the theatre, all things that just wouldn’t have gone well in the past.  But I still can’t believe how well he’s done today. I’ve cried a lot today. Happy tears. Of pride because I know how far he’s come ❤️ #autism #nonverbalautism #autismdad #autismmom #autismparents

E…Ds cannot be compartmentalized and often show up in our romantic relationships, influencing our thoughts and behaviours in various ways. Here are 3 common E..D thoughts I hear from clients: • “I keep comparing my body to their ex’s. Am I bigger than them? AM I thin/muscular enough? Do they think their ex was more attractive than me?” Remember, you are unique and valuable just as you are. Your partner’s past relationships are in the past for a reason. They chose to be with you now because of who you are, not because you resemble or differ from their ex. Focus on the connection you share and the reasons your partner appreciates you instead of physical appearances❤️ • “I don’t want my picture taken. What if I look too big? What if they notice flaws I see in myself?” It’s normal to feel self-conscious, but it’s important to remember that your partner wants to capture moments with you because they cherish you. Photos are memories of your shared experiences, not evaluations of your appearance. Your partner sees the beauty in you that goes beyond what any photo can capture.✨📸 • “I avoid wearing their clothes because I’m afraid I’ll be too big for them. What if I don’t fit? Will they think less of me?” Wearing each other’s clothes can be a fun way to feel close, but it’s not a measure of your worth or compatibility. Bodies come in all shapes and sizes, and clothing fit doesn’t define your relationship. Your partner loves you for who you are, not for how you fit into their wardrobe. If you feel like your E…D is taking a toll on your relationship, this is your sign to seek the help you need & deserve. - Z🧡  🌱Interested in individual therapy sessions? an aperitif for the olive oil obsessed 🫒  olive oil vermouth | test batch (2 servings) • 1/4 cup / 60ml high-quality extra virgin olive oil  • 1 cup / 250ml dry vermouth notes:  • you don’t need a top-tier finishing oil but the more fragrant and flavourful the olive oil is, the more fragrant and flavourful the vermouth will be. a good indication of what olive oil to use is if you can enjoy the olive oil on its own drizzled over bread. it must be 100% pure olive oil otherwise it will not freeze.  • important: use a fresh bottle of vermouth! vermouth is a fortified wine and begins to oxidize once opened. if its been sitting on your shelf for months, it’s time for a new bottle. always refrigerate your vermouth after opening and consume, ideally, within a month.  technique (24h infusion):  • pour olive oil and vermouth into a jar. close the lid and shake until well incorporated. leave to infuse at room temp for 1 hour. naturally, the oil will float to the top so remember to give it a good shake every 20mins for that first hour. • give it another shake before moving the jar to the fridge. shake whenever you remember.  • after the 24h infusion time, turn the jar upside down and freeze for another 2 hours. all freezers are different and yours may need a little less or more time. the goal is to freeze the olive oil but not the vermouth so that they can be easily separated.  • the olive oil should now be a solid disk, allowing you to easily pour the vermouth over a coffee filter for a final straining. the finished vermouth should have a fragrant olive oil scent and silky smooth mouthfeel.  drink chilled on its own or,  over ice for a slow dilution or,  highball with some sparkling water.  optional but a nice touch:  make some olive + olive brine ice cubes to get those dirty martini feels 🍸  #extravirginoliveoil #oliveoil #vermouth #aperitif #recipe #summerdrink #recipeoftheday #recipedeveloper

Dandruff vs. dry scalp: which one is it? |#BiolagePartner   It’s important to determine whether or not you have a dry scalp or dandruff (also known as seborrheic dermatitis) because the treatments are different. One is caused by the scalp producing less sebum resulting in the scalp surface becoming dry and flaky while the other (dandruff) is triggered by a yeast called Malassezia. So what do you do if you have a dry scalp? Exfoliate! Use a pre-shampoo treatment with glycolic acid like the Purifying Scalp Concentrate from @BIOLAGE (also has fermented tea too) + gentle shampoos and conditioners that help to restore balance in the scalp. Pasta in Italy IS different! .    I mean, authentic food always tastes better, right?! And many times different ingredients and drying processes are used which CAN impact things like gluten structure and amounts. If you have a gluten intolerance, yes, you might notice a difference in digestion! .    But there is also the fact that with decreased stress, slower paces of life, etc. digestion can improve. I'm not saying intolerances aren't real or that if you just stress less they'll go away. Absolutely NOT! But, for example, I used to get a tummy ache when I ate ice cream because it was a stress tummy ache over feeling guilty and like I shouldn't. Is that the case for everyone? No! But moral of this story is that stress over what you're eating can worsen digestion too! .   ❤️#nofoodrules #intuitiveeating #foodfreedom #nondiet #nutritiontips

“Other symptoms include lip smacking, eyelid fluttering, and chewing motions during these episodes.“ I wish these things were talked about more. At the time we thought it was just her “not responding” to her name which is a sign of ASD, but what makes this different is the fact that she isn’t occupied with something else, it’s like she just got lost. These seizures itself aren’t dangerous and most kids grow out of them BUT some kids can develop other types of seizures. Mikko does not have these as often as she did before.  These seizures can also look like a shut down, but remember that shut downs have triggers (being upset, traumatic experience etc..) absence seizures do not.  If you are concerned for your child, please talk with their pediatrician.  #asd #absenceseizures #autism #autismawareness #adhd #autismacceptance #specialneeds #autistic #autismmom #autismfamily #aspergers #autismspectrumdisorder #autismspectrum #autismsupport #autismlife #autismparents #autismlove #sensoryprocessingdisorder #differentnotless #neurodiversity #autismspeaks #autismdad #actuallyautistic #disability #autismo #anxiety #mentalhealth #downsyndrome #autismcommunity  #autismadvocate
