The story of autism luminary Temple Grandin 📖  Temple Grandin is a true inspiration for the autism community and beyond. Diagnosed with autism when it was barely understood, she overcame huge challenges and became a game-changer in animal science and autism advocacy. Temple’s work has helped break down myths about autism. Through her books and talks, she’s shown the world the importance of acceptance and inclusion. Her approach focuses on strengths and different learning styles, changing how we support people with autism. Let’s celebrate Temple’s amazing journey and her dedication to making the world better for everyone. Her story reminds us to embrace diversity and strive for a more inclusive society. 🫶  #actuallyautistic #autistic #autism #neurodiversity #neurodivergent #advocacy #spectrum #autismawareness #autisticmemes #autisticpride

some ways that autistiphobia and ableism show up inside (and of course outside) autistic communities ! 📢🌈 none of us are exempt from internalized ableism, and unfortunately that often comes at the expense of many HSN autistic folks, intersectional disability justice, and ultimately ourselves too. But that unpacking is necessary work - and when we are able to unlearn the influence of capitalism and all the isms telling us we are less than, we can start to truly believe that our value is not based on our ability to work or fit in with society - but inherent as humans with no extra conditions. And no, internalized ableism doesn’t disappear overnight, or even over years, but we can’t begin to address or rectify something if we can’t even acknowledge it exists! 👏 #intersectionality #disabilityinclusion #internalizedableism #senseofjustice #disabilityjustice #autisticsofcolor #autisticasian #ausian #neurodiversity #disabilityawareness #disabled #spd #autismtraits #autismawareness #autism #autisticadults #unmaskingautism #actuallyautistic #latediagnosedautistic

Replying to @Nursemitch let’s start normalizing the fact that autistic lifestyles do not  have to look like neurotypical ones, and thats okay! As an autistic person in a Neurotypical society, there is so much pressure to force my brain and body into a routine and lifestyle that’s designed for someone whose brain works totally different from me. Building an autistic lifestyle means listening to my brain and body, accommodating what I need, meeting those needs, really allowing myself to build my days in a way that aligns with my unique way of processing this world.  #autistic #autism #autisticadult #actuallyautistic #emilieleyes #neurodivergent #audhd

This morning the dogs prevented an epileptic seizure.  Echo immediately picked up scent and it almost looked like Everest did too. Typically, Everest goes off of Echo’s alert and responds by triggering the emergency button with his nose.  Echo brought rescue medication to prevent the seizure. Ruben received the call from the button and made sure I was okay.  Both dogs noticed I hadn’t taken the medication yet and each nudged my hand and pushed it towards me. I notified my list of caregivers of the incident with my seizure watch.  Once the seizure scent passed, Echo relaxed a bit and Everest celebrated with his Benebone.   This is why we record everything and travel with a home camera. It’s beneficial for advocacy and safety.  #ServiceDogs #SeizureResponseDogs #DisabilitySupport #SeizurePrevention #LifesavingDogs #EpilepsyAwareness

When should you use the term high functioning autism?  The majority of autistic people have been advocating for years to not use functioning labels. This is for a couple of important reasons. One being that we all have strengths and weaknesses just like anyone else. so we might be very "high functioning" in one area but need a lot of support in another.  The other reason is that functioning labels cause a lot more harm to the autistic community than they do good. often if someone is labeled low functioning, people just write them off and they often don't qualify for services that they might benefit from because of the low functioning label it is assumed they can't benefit from them. on the flip side of that, those who are considered high functioning, often still need a lot of support for certain things and are often denied help because "your functioning you don't need help you need to try harder" #autism #autistic #autismacceptance #autismawareness #autistictiktok #autisticcreator #functioninglabels

Today I got real personal, I shared something I thought I’d never have to.  The full video is in our Bio. Sensory Processing Disorder (SPD) is something I’ve dealt with all my life. Certain textiles, materials and visuals freak me out and it makes me wonder if my children are developing or dealing with the same thing... SPD is more than physical touch, it affects you mentally and emotionally as well. I think at some point in my life growing up, I understood what was going on which caused sensory overload to the point of me taking extreme measures to combat it. Some Autism symptoms can start and stop at any time, as you experience different things in life, you develop new stims, sensitivity’s and behaviors. Autism is a spectrum and it’s possible to have more than one medical condition accompanied along side like myself. Not only do I struggle with the nature of Autism and SPD, I also suffer from OCD, ADHD and Selective Mutism.  Although it’s a daily struggle, I continue to find the balance I need to keep going. #sensoryprocessingdisorder #autism #asd #autismawareness #adhd #specialneeds #spd #autismacceptance #aspergers #sensory #autismmom #anxiety #downsyndrome #autistic #disability #autismspectrumdisorder #autismlife #autismspectrum #occupationaltherapy #autismfamily #sensoryplay #autismsupport #specialneedsfamily #autismparent #autismdad #autismlove #autismparents #neurodiversity #differentnotless #autismcommunity

As we are entering the fall season, sports practices have started, homework is flooding in, and strict routines and rules are back. It’s hard for kids to go through so much change, especially when they are struggling with distractions and seeking extra sensory input.  At Pax we know how hard it is to watch your child struggle, which is why we want you to know we are here to help with a scan for sensory processing disorder! 💥  Electromyography (EMG) is a valuable diagnostic tool 📊 that can offer significant insights into understanding and addressing SPD in children. SPD can present a complex puzzle 🧩 for parents and healthcare providers, but EMG can provide a clearer picture of what's happening within their nervous system. 🧠 EMG measures the electrical activity of the neuromuscular 💪 system in response to sensory input. In the context of SPD, this means that EMG can help identify how a child's nervous system is responding to various sensory stimuli. It can reveal patterns of tension, relaxation, and energy 🔋 which can be indicative of how the child is processing sensory information. For instance, heightened neuromuscular tension may suggest that a child is experiencing sensory sensitivities, while weak muscle responses might indicate sensory-seeking behavior. ➡️ By incorporating EMG 📊 into the diagnostic process, parents can gain a more precise understanding of the child's sensory challenges. This insight helps guide our Neurologically-Focused Pediatric Chiropractors at Pax to develop a personalized care plan for your child and get you the hope, answers, and help you’ve been searching for.  While EMG is just one piece of the puzzle 🧩 in addressing SPD, it is a powerful tool and can act as a window into our child’s nervous system. 🧠 To read more about SPD and the EMG scan, visit the link 🔗 in our bio! And feel free to DM us to get your child scanned soon! ♥️ #spdtest  #spdinkids #sensoryissues #answerstospd #pxdocs

When should you use the term high functioning autism?  The majority of autistic people have been advocating for years to not use functioning labels. This is for a couple of important reasons. One being that we all have strengths and weaknesses just like anyone else. so we might be very "high functioning" in one area but need a lot of support in another.  The other reason is that functioning labels cause a lot more harm to the autistic community than they do good. often if someone is labeled low functioning, people just write them off and they often don't qualify for services that they might benefit from because of the low functioning label it is assumed they can't benefit from them. on the flip side of that, those who are considered high functioning, often still need a lot of support for certain things and are often denied help because "your functioning you don't need help you need to try harder" #autism #autistic #autismacceptance #autismawareness #autistictiktok #autisticcreator #functioninglabels

Take us back to march after being on a waiting list to get evaluated, we finally had our appointment & within 15 min my life felt like a ton of bricks on my shoulders & i kinda hid from the world and i was so overwhelmed with emotions. Especially being a single mom - i felt angry and sad that this would be a journey i would be embarking on my own with noone to be there for us. It took me a few months to come to terms with our new reality with a diagnosis and now all the windows of opportunity that will be available for my lil man. I promise to advocate for you till the very end ! Mama always got you  I'm not sad he's autistic. I'm sad he has to struggle so young and go through so much extra stuff. Recuerdo todos los días que hacía ejercicio yo le decía a mi hermana “quedaré bien Buena como tu” Jajajajaja pasando los meses yo veía como mi piel solo colgaba 😅 y decía  - No me quedará flacidez por qué hago mucho ejercicio- Cálmate 😂 que cuando llegue a pesar menos de 80kg mi pecho ya aprecia de señora mayor 🫣 me lleva casi al ombligo. Y yo solo me burlaba de él no me quedaba otra. Mis doctores, Nutriólogo, psicólogo y entrenadores siempre me dijeron que mi flacidez sería notoria y que tenía que prepararme y que ocuparía cirugía de reconstrucción☺️ desde el inicio me fueron muy sinceros y agradezco que gracias a eso nunca me hice falsas ilusiones. Y cada vez que bajaba más de peso mi flacidez se notaba más, yo solamente opté por fajarme ❤️ (Nadie sabía cómo había quedado mi cuerpo a pesar que ya había tenido una cirugía de reconstrucción por qué siempre me mostraba con fajas) Nunca me ha dado vergüenza y me he sentido libre pero eso no significa que me conformo a cómo va quedando mi cuerpo, cada día me esfuerzo y tengo un apoyo con mis cirugías de reconstrucción ❤️‍🩹 que gracias a todo he logrado mucho ❤️ #ejercicio #cirugia #salud #body #reconstrucción #cuerpo #bajardepeso

It’s quite common for toddlers to express reluctance towards certain tasks. You’ve probably encountered this scenario: you need your toddler to cooperate, but they resist. It’s a classic situation, am I right!? But don’t worry, as it’s a normal part of growing up!  In such moments, use your leverage wisely and withhold privileges until they do what you ask them to. This entails clearly communicating your expectations and consequences. Use a neutral tone of voice, and don’t ask them to do it— as that gives them the opportunity to say no. While I know this is easier said than done, do your best to try and stay calm and not to draw too much attention to what is happening— as nothing is more valuable than parental attention! Here are some other examples of moments your toddler may refuse to do something, but you have leverage: Situation: They want to go outside but won’t wear their jackets.  Solution: Don’t let them go outside until their jacket is on.  Situation: They want to use a new toy but won’t clean up.  Solution: They can’t play with new toys until they clean up.  Most importantly, reinforce your child when they engage in the appropriate behavior! Any time we want a behavior to increase or continue, it must be met with reinforcement!  #aba #appliedbehavioranalysis #behavior #parenting #parentsofinstagram #positiveparenting #parentingtips #toddlers #toddlersofinstagram #behaviormanagement #parentsupport #momssupportingmoms #newmom #momsofinstagram #parenttraining #parent #bcba #rbt #parentingishard #parentcoach #toddlertantrums #toddlermom #toddlermomlife #behavioranalysis #behavioranalyst #behaviors #parentingjourney #parentsbelike #teachersofinstagram #parenthood #parentsoftiktok #parenttok #fyp #foryou #toddlersoftiktok #toddlertok

Asking a disability attorney about their success rate or win rate is valueless information. Disability cases are apples and oranges. A lawyer who wins 90% of their cases doesn’t give you a 90% chance of being approved, it just means that they probably don’t challenge themselves. A much better strategy is to ask them what they would do to win your case. ##ssa##disability##ssi ##disabilitybenefits##Socialsecuritydisability##ssdi##disabilitylawyer##socialsecurity

Being black and autistic basically means that we don’t get to be weird and blame it on autism. Being black and autistic means that at every moment I have to be on guard and I have to put on a mask and be aware that I’m putting on a mask and constantly tweaking it based on the environment that I’m in it constantly suppressing because I can’t blame my weirdness on autism. it means that my autism can cause me to be an outcast and in my community that’s a danger because if you’re an outcast to your own community in the whole world already sees you as a threat that means you’re all alone and in danger.   #Autism #autizzy #neurospicy #autizzyasf #blackandautistic #actuallyautistic #audhd #autizzyaf #neurodivergent #rosaliespeaks

While the behaviors are often associated with Autism Spectrum Disorder (#ASD), it is an oversimplification to view them as definitive or exclusive symptoms. These behaviors reflect complex interactions of sensory, cognitive and social processing differences that vary widely among individuals with ASD. Planning Conversations People with ASD may meticulously plan conversations as a strategy to manage social anxiety and ensure predictability in interactions. This behavior is often a response to the discomfort they feel in social situations due to sensory overresponsivity (SOR) and the associated anxiety. Clumsiness or bumping into walls can be attributed to proprioceptive and vestibular processing difficulties common in ASD. These sensory challenges affect balance and spatial awareness, leading to increased incidents of physical clumsiness. Inflexibility and distress over changes in routine are hallmark traits of ASD. This behavior is linked to an intolerance of uncertainty, which can exacerbate anxiety and lead to extreme responses to deviations from expected plans. Sensory sensitivities, particularly to tactile stimuli, are common in individuals with ASD. These sensitivities can cause strong aversions to certain textures, such as microfiber, due to the heightened or altered sensory processing in these individuals. Discomfort with physical affection, such as hugging, often stems from sensory overresponsivity as well. Deep pressure touch, which can be soothing for some, may be overwhelming for individuals with ASD, leading them to avoid hugs and other forms of physical touch. These behaviors are manifestations of the unique #sensoryprocessing and social interaction challenges faced by individuals with ASD. Understanding these behaviors helps in providing better support and interventions tailored to the needs of those with #autism.

People who struggle with hoarding have difficulty letting go of possessions. Their living spaces become cluttered, disorganized, and often unfit for living in. While there can be different root causes of hoarding, one that is not very well known is that hoarding can be a behavior exhibited by people who are on the autism spectrum, including people with masked autism. In these cases, hoarding results from issues with emotional regulation, sensory regulation, and executive functioning. Ayudianews-' Kabar duka datang dari ibunda Naja Hudia, anak istimewa yang jadi hafiz Al-Qur'an tahun 2019. Bocah asal Mataram, Nusa Tenggara Barat (NTB) ini memiliki keterbatasan fisik karena penyakit cerebral palsy atau lumpuh otak yang dideritanya. Meski fisiknya tidak sempurna dan harus beraktivitas di atas kursi roda, namun Naja mampu menghafalkan 30 juz Al-Qur'an. Kabar meninggalnya Dahlia Andayani, ibunda Naja ini viral di media sosial dan mencuri perhatian warganet. Banyak yang ikut merasa sedih atas meninggalnya ibunda Naja. Ini sosok Naja Hudia hafiz Indonesia yang 'istimewa'. #naja #meninggaldunia #kabarduka #viral #fyp

Have you heard of Ehlers-Danlos Syndromes/Hypermobility Spectrum Disorders (EDS/HSD) or Postural Orthostatic Tachycardia Syndrome (POTS)?  Considerable interest has arisen concerning the high rate of cooccurence between hereditary connective tissue disorders such as the Ehlers-Danlos syndromes (EDS)/hypermobility spectrum disorders (HSD) and Autism. The overlap between these two spectrum conditions, including neurobehavioural, psychiatric, and neurological commonalities, shared peripheral neuropathies and neuropathologies, and similar autonomic and immune dysregulation suggest that EDS/HSD may represent a subtype of Autism. Today we are joined by Dr. Emily Casanova. Emily has a research background in neurobiology, developmental biology with particular foci on Autism, and connective tissue disorders like EDS and HSD. She is passionate about patient advocacy for individuals with chronic and/or rare illnesses and lived experience of Autism, EDS, and HSD.    Emily is featured in Module 3 of The Autism & Neurodiversity MasterClass where we deep dive into what Autism actually is, the science, the history, Spikey Skills and Colour Wheels, the Autism and ADHD overlap, PDA and a number of co-occuring conditions like EDS, HSD and POTS. Know your rights. Know your disability. Be a strong self advocate.  Learn how by listening to 28 of the best. ⭐️check out the 🔗 in my profile👆 to read my blog post about autism stimming ❤️ Stimming is a behavior commonly associated with autism spectrum disorder (ASD). Stimming refers to self-stimulatory behaviors or repetitive movements that individuals with autism engage in. These behaviors can include hand flapping, rocking back and forth, spinning, or making repetitive sounds or vocalizations. Stimming serves different purposes for different individuals. It can help regulate sensory input, provide a sense of comfort, alleviate anxiety, or express excitement or joy ❤️❤️ #autism #autistic #specialneedsparenting #stimming #parenting #sensory #fyp

Accessible Rest for Neurodivergent Individuals > Self-Regulation > Levels If you are neurodivergent, have chronic fatigue, fibromyalgia, POTS, PTSD, cPTSD or any other nervous system dysfunction or irregularity this video might help explain why you can’t seem to access typical regulation strategies.  Here is a summary: Level 1: Focus on the environment and indulgence. FOG = Fear, obligation, guilt. You want the following to be “FOG-free”. Once you can access these strategies FOG-free, you can begin to shift into Level 2 Level 1 Examples:  Yummy food Cat videos Scrolling funny videos Calming video games like Stardew Valley or Minecraft Aromatherapy  Soft blankets Cozy Jammies Level 2: Focus on body-specific strategies that give vestibular or proprioceptive input. Think: Deep pressure. Once you can access these AND include Level 1 strategies simultaneously, start shifting into Level 3. Level 2 Examples: Deep stretching Massage Swinging Walk in nature Water (swimming, bath, etc.) Weighted blanket You will want to consistently start at Level 1 and work your way through the levels each time you need to regulate. While I was never bothered social questions as an autistic kid myself…SO MANY of my clients are.  They just don’t find connection that way. 🤷🏼‍♀️ 📝 Through my 9 years of clinical experience supporting kids on the autism spectrum…here’s some things to try instead: ▪️ Use open body language to show you’re available ▪️Narrate/describe their actions ▪️Play with similar objects nearby  ▪️Follow the child’s lead ▪️Be responsive to their movements, sounds, and words ▪️Make STATEMENTS about what you see/hear/feel/think  #autistic #autism #aba #autismacceptance #autismawareness #therapist #neruodivergent #pda #autismmom #therapy

But as I say with all projects that don’t go perfectly (which is all projects), it just ads character 😅. Seriously though, I’m loving this little thrift flip and I want to do it for different holidays and occasions.  Here’s how I made it: •I melted down the candle (in a cheap pot I got from the thrift store) •I added several drops (that’s about as specific as I know how to be here 😅) of magnolia, wild orange, and grapefruit essential oils because this candle was unscented •I glued candle wicks to the dish which more or less kept them in place •I poured the melted candle wax into the dish  •I added dried flowers to the dish and then added a few more once it had cooled off a bit because the first ones all sunk to the bottom Total cost: $1.75 (not including the essential oils I already had) #thriftflip #thrifting #thriftdiy #candlemaking #thriftedcandle #driedflowers #driedflowerscrafts #diy #candlediy #handmade #thrifty #thriftfinds #homedecor #seasonaldecor

Did you know when choosing between doing a flexi rod set on wet hair versus blow-dried hair, there are a few key differences to consider: Flexi Rod Set on Wet Hair: -Better Definition: Curls tend to be more defined when set on wet hair. -Longer Lasting: Wet sets generally last longer because the hair dries into the shape of the curls. -Longer Drying Time: Wet hair takes longer to dry, especially if air-drying. This can be inconvenient. - Shrinkage: Wet hair tends to shrink as it dries, which may result in shorter curls than expected. Flexi Rod Set on Blow-Dried Hair: -Quicker Drying Time: Hair is already dry, so the setting process is faster. -More Length: Blow-dried hair generally has less shrinkage, resulting in longer-looking curls. -Smoother Finish: Blow-drying can help achieve a smoother look by reducing frizz before setting the hair. -Less Definition: Curls may be less defined compared to a wet set. -Shorter Lasting: Curls may not last as long as those set on wet hair. I don’t know about you but the older I get, the less time I want to spend styling my hair.. Comfort became a key consideration as I aged, and hairstyles that are easy to manage aligned with this priority so perfectly.  We all have different competing demands on our time, and what is considered “hard to manage” or “time-consuming” is different for different people.  One thing I know for sure is that switching to wearing clip-ins has not only shortened my styling days but has been so easy to manage! Clip-in extensions are temporary and can be easily clipped in and out of your natural hair (especially if you have a braid down). This means you can change your hairstyle or hair length without committing to a permanent change. Applying clip-in extensions takes a relatively short amount of time compared to other types of hair extensions too (sew-ins, tapes, even quick weaves) What about you? Do you find wearing clip-ins fast and easy to manage? Despite what our youth obsessed society tries to tell us, it’s ok to LOOK OUR AGE. We enter our midlife years with compliments flowing around “not looking our age”.  That aspiring to look younger than our age is a base level expectation assumed of every woman entering the different seasons of her life.  A narrative that plays so perfectly into the hands of the lucrative 62-billion dollar anti-ageing industry. Age = less Youth = more BUT Embracing our age unapologetically with confidence does not imply a personal failure to defy our body’s natural ageing process.  Our value and worth as complex humans does not change or decline depending on our trips around the sun or the depth of crinkles on our bodies.  At 52 years old, I’m finally starting to give my body the peace and acceptance it has always deserved.  This body was never flawed, broken or in need of repair.  This body is a unique and resilient vessel that allows me to experience the world. It is imperfectly etched with the stories, emotions and experiences of a life well lived.  I am proud to reach this unapologetic age and see it through much kinder and compassionate eyes.  Eyes that don’t compare or critique or use society’s youth beauty standards as a measuring stick.  Eyes that instead look for beauty in wisdom, strength, compassion, determination, experience, joy and the raw and real. I’m 52 years old.  and proud to say… I LOOK MY AGE.  Thank you @agismisneverinstyle for another wonderful age positive campaign challenging ageism, changing the narrative around ageing and improving over 50 representation in fashion and the media. #ilookmyage

Today I got real personal, I shared something I thought I’d never have to.  The full video is in our Bio. Sensory Processing Disorder (SPD) is something I’ve dealt with all my life. Certain textiles, materials and visuals freak me out and it makes me wonder if my children are developing or dealing with the same thing... SPD is more than physical touch, it affects you mentally and emotionally as well. I think at some point in my life growing up, I understood what was going on which caused sensory overload to the point of me taking extreme measures to combat it. Some Autism symptoms can start and stop at any time, as you experience different things in life, you develop new stims, sensitivity’s and behaviors. Autism is a spectrum and it’s possible to have more than one medical condition accompanied along side like myself. Not only do I struggle with the nature of Autism and SPD, I also suffer from OCD, ADHD and Selective Mutism.  Although it’s a daily struggle, I continue to find the balance I need to keep going. #sensoryprocessingdisorder #autism #asd #autismawareness #adhd #specialneeds #spd #autismacceptance #aspergers #sensory #autismmom #anxiety #downsyndrome #autistic #disability #autismspectrumdisorder #autismlife #autismspectrum #occupationaltherapy #autismfamily #sensoryplay #autismsupport #specialneedsfamily #autismparent #autismdad #autismlove #autismparents #neurodiversity #differentnotless #autismcommunity

Did you know when choosing between doing a flexi rod set on wet hair versus blow-dried hair, there are a few key differences to consider: Flexi Rod Set on Wet Hair: -Better Definition: Curls tend to be more defined when set on wet hair. -Longer Lasting: Wet sets generally last longer because the hair dries into the shape of the curls. -Longer Drying Time: Wet hair takes longer to dry, especially if air-drying. This can be inconvenient. - Shrinkage: Wet hair tends to shrink as it dries, which may result in shorter curls than expected. Flexi Rod Set on Blow-Dried Hair: -Quicker Drying Time: Hair is already dry, so the setting process is faster. -More Length: Blow-dried hair generally has less shrinkage, resulting in longer-looking curls. -Smoother Finish: Blow-drying can help achieve a smoother look by reducing frizz before setting the hair. -Less Definition: Curls may be less defined compared to a wet set. -Shorter Lasting: Curls may not last as long as those set on wet hair. Would you like tips on how to execute each method or recommendations on products to use? #detroitstylist #detroithair #voiceofhair #detroithairstylist #naturalhair #luxurayhair #behindthechair #blackhair #detroitblogger #hypehair #curlyhairdontcare #detroitnaturalhairstylist

I know a lot of people will more so criticize the fact that I am speaking of age in months rather than year so I’m going to address it, so that we all can focus on the actual message of the video.  The distinctions between a 13-month-old and a 21-month-old—both “1” if measured in years—can be dramatic. So pediatricians use small increments to check developmental milestones. So many different changes happen very quickly. This is how a child under 3 is evaluated.  This was Mikko first evaluation before her Autism diagnosis. Something I had already expected and observed for quite some time. These results were very alarming and scary for me at first. This is when I decided to fully focus on helping her the best way I could at home. A quincunx to the Pisces Moon creates a subtle but noticeable tension between your emotional needs and your relationships. You may feel out of sync with those around you, as though what you need emotionally doesn’t quite align with the expectations or desires of others. Pluto doesn’t allow for superficiality, and this aspect will push you to speak with honesty and depth, even if it feels uncomfortable. Finally, the square between Venus and Pluto adds a layer of complexity to your relationships. There’s an undercurrent of tension, as issues of trust, control, and emotional power come to the forefront. This is a time to confront those dynamics head-on, to address the unspoken truths that have been shaping your interactions. There’s a need for honesty here, even if it feels raw or vulnerable. As this eclipse passes, you’ll find that what’s been revealed isn’t so much a shock as it is a gentle unveiling. You are being asked to step into a deeper understanding of yourself and to trust in the process of change, not as something to be feared, but as something to be embraced. The awareness this eclipse brings is subtle, yet profound, offering you a chance to realign with who you truly are beneath the layers of illusion and avoidance. AUTISM JOURNEY: WHY IS AUTISM EVERYWHERE NOW?  This of course may not be the only reason, but from my personal cultural experience, from things unsaid with my own family when growing up. Things we pretended not to see because we didn’t have a name for it, so it was often easier to blame witchcraft, the devil or dismiss it as just “madness”.  Awareness is so important, it shapes so much of how we see others and most importantly how we choose to move and the help we get.  Silly analogy here- but I suffered from sleep paralysis for a long time and growing up there was no name for it and I felt alone and cursed. I would cry and pray and think I was being dragged to hell. That was until I read about sleep paralysis as an actually relatively common sleep disorder and how simple healthier sleep habits and diet could diminish and altogether stop them. It’s hard when you don’t know what’s happening and if you don’t have a name, you don’t have a course of action, you don’t even know that treatments and help exist. So that’s why awareness is important and with increased awareness, there’s more people saying… wait a minute I finally understand what I’ve been going through, I finally understand what my child is going through.  There’s probably still an important conversation about all the external factors that may be increasing autism numbers- but let’s not pretend that all this is new simply because we called it something else before. #AutismVolumes #autismmom #autismfamily #autismvolumes #autismawareness #autismisbeautiful #autism #autismspectrum #autismsupport #autismparent #onthespectrum #neurodiversity #autistickids #blackautismawareness #autismawarenessmonth

While I was never bothered social questions as an autistic kid myself…SO MANY of my clients are.  They just don’t find connection that way. 🤷🏼‍♀️ 📝 Through my 9 years of clinical experience supporting kids on the autism spectrum…here’s some things to try instead: ▪️ Use open body language to show you’re available ▪️Narrate/describe their actions ▪️Play with similar objects nearby  ▪️Follow the child’s lead ▪️Be responsive to their movements, sounds, and words ▪️Make STATEMENTS about what you see/hear/feel/think  #autistic #autism #aba #autismacceptance #autismawareness #therapist #neruodivergent #pda #autismmom #therapy

Replying to @Natalie Rayne autism is the source of my struggles but it is ALSO the source of so much of my joy! Autism is a neotype, which means that it informs every single piece of my lived experience, good and bad. It amplifies the positive, it’s the source of my strengths and talents, and it is the reason why I am who I am!  And of *course* I could go on and on and on about the challenges that I experienced, and I don’t want this video to be perceived as me pretending like I don’t have challenges or like being autistic  is wonderful all the time. I face a lot of hard stuff that isnt shown on camera. ❌ DAY 9 OF REJECTION THERAPY ❌ This was one of the challenges I was dreading THE MOST! 😅 I’ve done it a few times before but never for $100 so it felt edgy to put it lightly. Here’s what I learned: The anticipation of the thing is often worse than the thing itself. My pulse was racing. My hands were clammy. And as soon as it was over, I came back to baseline. You sitting in indecision, waiting for the perfect moment and for the stars to align is what is CAUSING your anxiety… not the fear of doing the thing itself. 🙃 The longer you sit in indecision, the more intense your fear becomes until eventually it has you in a chokehold and you feel paralysed. So whatever that thing is that you’re sitting on… go do it. Do it now. What are you ACTUALLY waiting for? 🤔 For you to feel no fear? Feel completely confident? You may be waiting a while. So do the thing scared. But do the thing nonetheless. 🫶🏼 #rejectiontherapy #confidenceiskey #rejection #30daychallenge

Have you heard of Ehlers-Danlos Syndromes/Hypermobility Spectrum Disorders (EDS/HSD) or Postural Orthostatic Tachycardia Syndrome (POTS)?  Considerable interest has arisen concerning the high rate of cooccurence between hereditary connective tissue disorders such as the Ehlers-Danlos syndromes (EDS)/hypermobility spectrum disorders (HSD) and Autism. The overlap between these two spectrum conditions, including neurobehavioural, psychiatric, and neurological commonalities, shared peripheral neuropathies and neuropathologies, and similar autonomic and immune dysregulation suggest that EDS/HSD may represent a subtype of Autism. Today we are joined by Dr. Emily Casanova. Emily has a research background in neurobiology, developmental biology with particular foci on Autism, and connective tissue disorders like EDS and HSD. She is passionate about patient advocacy for individuals with chronic and/or rare illnesses and lived experience of Autism, EDS, and HSD.    Emily is featured in Module 3 of The Autism & Neurodiversity MasterClass where we deep dive into what Autism actually is, the science, the history, Spikey Skills and Colour Wheels, the Autism and ADHD overlap, PDA and a number of co-occuring conditions like EDS, HSD and POTS. 😬 this is a very unhelpful response some parents have to seeing their kids struggle with their mental health.  If your kid opens up to you about their mental health struggles, try not to make it about you. Avoid using guilt in an attempt to motivate or manipulate your child into feeling better or acting differently. It won’t work and will likely just make them feel even more guilty and alone. Remember, you can be the world’s best parent and your kid may still struggle with their mental health. But we all make mistakes and what is important is owning up to it and working on changing what you need to change. And if you do feel guilt about your child’s struggles, talk with another adult (especially a mental health professional!) about those feelings. If your child is already dealing with difficult feelings, the last thing you want to do is force them to manage your emotions as well. #depressionhelp #mentalhealthmatters

What you can do to support them: The key is to support or ask for help in a way that doesn't feel overwhelming or exhausting for them. Here are some examples: - I was thinking of watching a new movie tonight, and I'd love your company. Do you mind if I come over with snacks? We can just relax and enjoy the it together. - I'm trying out different tea blends and could really use your help to choose the best one. Want to join me for a tea tasting session? - There’s a new cafe that opened up nearby, and I heard they have great coffee. Want to check it out with me? My treat! - It's a great evening for a drive. How about we just cruise around for a bit while listening to some good music? I can pick you up in an hour! Keep in mind that, sometimes, they might not be up to hosting at their place if they think it’s untidy, and going out might seem overwhelming if it requires a lot of preparation or too much energy. So opt for activities that are simple and enjoyable — things that won't drain their energy but will genuinely make them feel included and valued. This way, you offer support without adding pressure. The story of autism luminary Temple Grandin 📖  Temple Grandin is a true inspiration for the autism community and beyond. Diagnosed with autism when it was barely understood, she overcame huge challenges and became a game-changer in animal science and autism advocacy. Temple’s work has helped break down myths about autism. Through her books and talks, she’s shown the world the importance of acceptance and inclusion. Her approach focuses on strengths and different learning styles, changing how we support people with autism. Let’s celebrate Temple’s amazing journey and her dedication to making the world better for everyone. Her story reminds us to embrace diversity and strive for a more inclusive society. 🫶  #actuallyautistic #autistic #autism #neurodiversity #neurodivergent #advocacy #spectrum #autismawareness #autisticmemes #autisticpride

So we’re excited to be working with @SupportTheSpectrum and Ryann who had some great videos on understanding how some with Autism acquire language. she talks about echolalia, delayed echolalia, and Gestalt language processors showing examples of each. I’ve always known that Abbey accesses memories before words, but I never quite understood this term ‘Gestalt language processor.’   The more I have learned about it the more I can see the connection to her language and memories and how the brain can get stuck in memories before descriptive language. This is a huge break for me to better understand how abbey’s mind works so i can  assist with language on her terms. I know some here will say ‘what’s the big deal let Abbey speak in memories ‘ and that’s fine if that’s their choice for their loved  one. But my goal is to have Abbey be independent, be able to self advocate, and be able to be heard in the world after I’m gone. So for parents with those struggling with language in autism, look to see if memories are being used to describe feelings and then follow Ryann’s page to learn more to see how you can be supporting your loved one in language development. @Abb@Abbeyb#abbeysautism

🔺 Hay Personas Que Son Autistas y No Lo Saben (TEA) I Bajo Tu Punto De Vista🔺 ✄---------  Puede que algunas personas lleguen a la edad adulta sin darse cuenta de que son autistas. Esto puede suceder por varias razones:  - Diferencias individuales: El espectro autista es muy amplio y variado. Algunas personas pueden tener síntomas más leves o menos evidentes, lo que puede dificultar el reconocimiento del autismo, especialmente si no han sido evaluadas en la infancia.  - Falta de conciencia y educación sobre el autismo: En el pasado, el autismo no siempre se entendía bien y no se diagnosticaba con la misma frecuencia que hoy en día. Las personas pueden haber pasado desapercibidas o malinterpretado sus diferencias como simples peculiaridades de personalidad.  - Cambio en las circunstancias de la vida: Algunas personas pueden haber desarrollado estrategias de afrontamiento para lidiar con sus diferencias mientras crecían, lo que les permitió funcionar relativamente bien en entornos específicos. Sin embargo, pueden comenzar a notar más dificultades o diferencias a medida que enfrentan nuevas situaciones o responsabilidades en la edad adulta.  - Mayor conciencia y comprensión del autismo en la sociedad: A medida que la conciencia y la comprensión del autismo han aumentado en los últimos años, más adultos pueden reconocer síntomas autistas en sí mismos a través de información en línea, testimonios de otras personas autistas o la experiencia de ser padres de niños diagnosticados con TEA.  Cuando los adultos se dan cuenta de que pueden ser autistas, a menudo buscan evaluaciones y diagnósticos para obtener claridad sobre su identidad y comprender mejor sus necesidades y experiencias. Es importante destacar que el diagnóstico de autismo en la edad adulta es válido y puede ser increíblemente útil para acceder a apoyos y recursos que pueden mejorar la calidad de vida. ✄--------- #bajotupuntodevista #podcast #podcastclipsviral #podcaster #podcastiktok #autismo #autism #tea #trastornodelespectroautistas #asperger #síndromedeasperger  #paratiiii #fyp #explore #tiktokpodcaster

Zespół Aspergera to zaburzenie ze spektrum autyzmu, które charakteryzuje się trudnościami w interakcjach społecznych i komunikacji, a także specyficznymi, często intensywnymi zainteresowaniami i powtarzającymi się zachowaniami. Osoby z zespołem Aspergera mogą mieć trudności z rozumieniem norm społecznych, interpretacją mimiki, gestów czy tonacji głosu innych ludzi. Często mają również trudności w nawiązywaniu i utrzymywaniu relacji międzyludzkich. W przeciwieństwie do klasycznego autyzmu, osoby z zespołem Aspergera zazwyczaj nie mają opóźnień w rozwoju mowy i inteligencji, a często wykazują przeciętny lub wysoki poziom intelektualny. Ich język może być jednak formalny lub pedantyczny. Ponadto mogą wykazywać skłonność do rutyny i potrzebę przewidywalności. Zespół Aspergera jest obecnie klasyfikowany jako część spektrum autyzmu, a nie jako oddzielne zaburzenie, co oznacza, że różne osoby mogą wykazywać różne nasilenie objawów. Wsparcie dla osób z zespołem Aspergera często koncentruje się na nauce umiejętności społecznych, terapii behawioralnej oraz wsparciu w radzeniu sobie z codziennymi wyzwaniami. #asperger #rozwójmowy #obserwujmnie #codziennośćmamy #macierzyństwo #codziennośćrodzica #autyzm #autyzmpolska #autyzmnawesoło #autyzmnietakistraszny #mamdzieckozautyzmem #mamdzieckozniepełnosprawnością #adhd #wsparcie #wsparcierodzicielskie #wsparciepsychiczne #pogadanka

🚨 Struggling with School? Act NOW to Support Your Child’s Success! 🚨 We’re only a few months into the school year, but if your child is still struggling… don’t wait to take action! 💡 Schools can take a long time to make changes, so if you don’t start the process now, you could be looking at an entire year without progress. Let’s change that! 🛠️ Here are 4 pro-tips to help you get your child the support they need: 1️⃣ Get everything in writing! After any phone call with the school, follow up with an email starting with “per our conversation.” Documentation is key! ✍️ 2️⃣ Request an assessment. Don’t wait for an official diagnosis—schools can assess your child without one. Ask for it in writing! 🔍 3️⃣ Call for an IEP meeting if your child already has one but is still struggling. It’s time to make adjustments that actually help! 📝 4️⃣ If none of the above work, it’s time to consider a special education advocate or attorney. Your child deserves the right support, and you shouldn’t have to pick them up from school every day due to behavior struggles. 💼 👉 Be sure to save this video to reference so you always know what steps you need to take next! #AutismJumpstart #SchoolStruggles #SpecialEducation #IEPTips #AdvocacyForKids #ParentEmpowerment #AutismSupport #EarlyIntervention #EducationMatters #AutismParents #AutismJourney #ChildAdvocacy #AutismAwareness #IEP #specialeducation

“Other symptoms include lip smacking, eyelid fluttering, and chewing motions during these episodes.“ I wish these things were talked about more. At the time we thought it was just her “not responding” to her name which is a sign of ASD, but what makes this different is the fact that she isn’t occupied with something else, it’s like she just got lost. These seizures itself aren’t dangerous and most kids grow out of them BUT some kids can develop other types of seizures. Mikko does not have these as often as she did before.  These seizures can also look like a shut down, but remember that shut downs have triggers (being upset, traumatic experience etc..) absence seizures do not.  If you are concerned for your child, please talk with their pediatrician.  #asd #absenceseizures #autism #autismawareness #adhd #autismacceptance #specialneeds #autistic #autismmom #autismfamily #aspergers #autismspectrumdisorder #autismspectrum #autismsupport #autismlife #autismparents #autismlove #sensoryprocessingdisorder #differentnotless #neurodiversity #autismspeaks #autismdad #actuallyautistic #disability #autismo #anxiety #mentalhealth #downsyndrome #autismcommunity  #autismadvocate

As you know Mikko stims a lot. Sucking her thumb and hair twirling is her go to for comfort. Even before we knew what Autism stimming was, This was always her thing since she was 3 months old. She didn’t quite like the pacifier and only really found comfort in her hands.  Thumb sucking can cause major dental issues with how her mouth is forming as she grows and because she is nonverbal, I fear that it can also hinder how she learns to communicates. Although this may be working at the moment, we are actively working toward a more permanent solution. Stimming is something that will naturally change as she grows, we just want to make sure it does not turn into a different unhealthy habit. #asd #autism #autismawareness #adhd #autismacceptance #specialneeds #autistic #autismmom #autismfamily #aspergers #autismspectrumdisorder #autismspectrum #autismsupport #autismlife #autismparents #autismlove #sensoryprocessingdisorder #differentnotless #neurodiversity #autismspeaks #autismdad #actuallyautistic #disability #autismo #anxiety #mentalhealth #downsyndrome #autismcommunity #love #autismadvocate

As speech therapists, we know the incredible power of AAC devices in giving children a way to communicate. These tools don’t hinder spoken language—they enhance it, empowering those whose primary form of communication is not through spoken words. It can be disheartening when people overlook the importance of these devices, seeing them as less valuable than spoken words. But every form of communication is worthy and valid! Let’s continue to honor and respect all ways of expressing oneself, because using mouth words isn’t the only way to be heard. 💬 #AACAwareness #SpeechTherapy #InclusiveCommunication #CommunicationMatters #SLPcommunity #AACSupport #AugmentativeAndAlternativeCommunication #SpeechLanguagePathologist #CommunicationDiversity #AssistiveTechnology #SpeechDevelopment #SpeechPathology #SLPadvocate #CommunicationIsKey #nonverbalcommunication

She had such a hard time focusing and paying attention as she was always in her own world. Musical and performance arts really helped Abbey connect and build confidence. She has worked so hard to get where she is today. None of this was easy for her, but she never gave up. Just seeing her on stage today brings tears to our eyes thinking about the journey and what she has overcome to get here. #abbeysautism

I used to think that a self diagnosis was not okay. Why? Because I thought it was kinda a slap in the face to those who were diagnosed autistic. But oh how my thought process has changed!!! I recently went for an autism diagnosis after hours and hours of researching on the internet about autism and how it presents in women. The outcome? Well the evaluator told me that I had all the autistic traits in all areas with sensory scoring the highest but BECAUSE my functioning levels are fine and I’m living life just fine (not handicap) 🥴, I did not meet the criteria for the autism diagnosis. But that I should identify as autistic and was given autism support groups to join. So now if you’d ask me if I support a self diagnosis I would say 100% not just because of situations like mine but for other reasons like money (it’s super expensive), not everyone has the resources, grown adults who have lived their entire lives undiagnosed and now just know, and honestly so many other reason that don’t need to be listed or even explained. Because you don’t need to explain anything to anyone. Your feelings are valid! What you go through is valid!!! 💖 #autisminwomen #actuallyautistic  #autismfamily #autismcommunity #neurodivergentcommunity #neurodivergent #selfdiagnosis

It makes me sad, but one thing for sure my parents will always leave things in place for me, I have an amazing support system! SO THAT MAKES ME 😊. So fam, don't hesitate,  start putting things in place and getting that "village " together. At first it use to bother me because I am an intentional mother and I go hard for my children. I originally didn’t want to share my family but God lead me to do so for his Glory and purpose. Today reading peoples rude comments don’t bother me like they use to and I thank God for building me up. I would absolutely love to have one more baby. Having children is such a beautiful experience especially when you do it with Jesus and with a husband who is hands on and extremely supportive. It amazes me to see what is in people hearts when they see my family. I thank God for his unconditional love and for his hand on my family.  It isn’t my family they hate but the image. . 👇Stress hormones ruining your sleep? If you struggle with sleepless nights, heightened anxiety, frequent bathroom trips, and those dreaded 3 AM wake-ups…  High cortisol levels could be to blame.  Here’s how this stress hormone wreaks havoc on your rest and disrupts your natural circadian rhythm: 1. It Keeps You Up at Night: Elevated cortisol makes you feel alert and restless, making it hard to fall and stay asleep. 2. It Increases Anxiety: High cortisol amps up anxiety, causing your mind to race with worries and what-ifs. 3. Frequent Bathroom Trips: Cortisol can increase fluid retention and urinary urgency, making you get up multiple times to pee. 4. 3 AM Wake-Ups: Cortisol levels can spike in the early morning hours, jolting you awake and making it hard to fall back asleep. 5. It Disrupts Circadian Rhythm: Cortisol naturally peaks in the morning to help you wake up and gradually decreases throughout the day. When dysregulated, you feel tired during the day but wide awake at night, disrupting your natural sleep-wake cycle. To combat this, you must learn how to train your nervous system to feel calm during the day so it naturally helps you stay calm and sleep at night. 100 formas de hacer papas - #62 Tater Tots Seguimos con la serie de 100 recetas diferentes con papas. SÍ, 100 recetas Hoy, un acompañamiento clásico de las comidas norteamericanas: tater tots. Una forma de comer papas que mezcla la papa frita con el hash brown, los tater tots son estos bocaditos ultra crujientes y que son ideales como acompañamiento (en lugar de las típicas papas fritas) o como una muy buena entrada. Un plato muy común de los dinners estadounidenses pero mucho más popular en la sección congelados de cualquier supermercado para hacerlos en casa (de hecho, los pueden congelar en crudo y guardarlos). El éxito de esta receta, para mí, es que combina lo mejor de los dos mundos entre una tortita de papa y una papa frita!  PREPARACIÓN 1) Pelar y rallar (por la parte gruesa del rallador) 500 grs de papa (si es para fritura mejor, pero funciona con cualquier variedad). Llevar a una olla con agua a punto de hervir y pre cocinarla por 5 minutos, no más y sin que el agua rompa hervor. Colar y llevar a un bol. 2) Dejar enfríar (si están apurados pueden pasarla directamente por agua fría para que enfríe rápido) y exprimir muuuuy bien quitándole todo el líquido sobrante (yo usé una malla, pueden usar un repasador, o las manos). Condimentar con sal, pimienta y ajo en polvo y agregar dos o tres cucharadas de fécula de maíz hasta que la mezcla tome forma homogénea. 3) Formar bolitas tamaño bocado, llevar a una placa y mandar al freezer o congelador hasta que estén bien congeladas (fundamental para que no se desarmen luego) 4) Para la barbacoa: 2 tazas de ketchup, 3 cdas grandes de azúcar mascabo, un chorro de vinagre, salsa inglesa y agua, 2 cditas de miel, y ajo en polvo. Cocinar a fuego bajo hasta que reduzca. 5) Para cocinar los tater tots, llevarlos directo del freezer al aceite bien caliente (que burbujee bien, 180º). Cocinar 3 minutos hasta que tomen color, retirar, escurrir, servir y disfrutar! #asmrfood #100formasdehacerpapas #fyp #foodlover #potatotiktok #papas #recetas #tatertots

The not-so-full story of how I get formally diagnosed with ASD at the age of 29. Bismillah. I’m sharing my journey with intention to give awareness that autistic adults struggle too and we do need accommodation, ongoing support and access to treatment. However, the gap in obtaining a formal diagnosis has hindered so many autistic individuals from receiving the support they deserve. My sensory processing difficulties has impacted many areas of my life. My hidden struggle with social communication has caused a lot of mental health issues. I grew up without knowing about my condition and have tried so many methods mindlessly. But this new insight has healed so many parts of me. When I was informed of my difficulties, I become more aware of the strategies to navigate life challenges.  It wasn’t a smooth sailing journey. It involves years.. no, decades of confusion and history of reaching out for help. Alhamdulillah for where I am now.  #autismawareness #autisticadult #actuallyautistic #sensoryprocessing #formaldiagnosis

As you know Mikko stims a lot. Sucking her thumb and hair twirling is her go to for comfort. Even before we knew what Autism stimming was, This was always her thing since she was 3 months old. She didn’t quite like the pacifier and only really found comfort in her hands.  Thumb sucking can cause major dental issues with how her mouth is forming as she grows and because she is nonverbal, I fear that it can also hinder how she learns to communicates. Although this may be working at the moment, we are actively working toward a more permanent solution. Stimming is something that will naturally change as she grows, we just want to make sure it does not turn into a different unhealthy habit. #asd #autism #autismawareness #adhd #autismacceptance #specialneeds #autistic #autismmom #autismfamily #aspergers #autismspectrumdisorder #autismspectrum #autismsupport #autismlife #autismparents #autismlove #sensoryprocessingdisorder #differentnotless #neurodiversity #autismspeaks #autismdad #actuallyautistic #disability #autismo #anxiety #mentalhealth #downsyndrome #autismcommunity #love #autismadvocate

🚨 Struggling with School? Act NOW to Support Your Child’s Success! 🚨 We’re only a few months into the school year, but if your child is still struggling… don’t wait to take action! 💡 Schools can take a long time to make changes, so if you don’t start the process now, you could be looking at an entire year without progress. Let’s change that! 🛠️ Here are 4 pro-tips to help you get your child the support they need: 1️⃣ Get everything in writing! After any phone call with the school, follow up with an email starting with “per our conversation.” Documentation is key! ✍️ 2️⃣ Request an assessment. Don’t wait for an official diagnosis—schools can assess your child without one. Ask for it in writing! 🔍 3️⃣ Call for an IEP meeting if your child already has one but is still struggling. It’s time to make adjustments that actually help! 📝 4️⃣ If none of the above work, it’s time to consider a special education advocate or attorney. Your child deserves the right support, and you shouldn’t have to pick them up from school every day due to behavior struggles. 💼 👉 Be sure to save this video to reference so you always know what steps you need to take next! #AutismJumpstart #SchoolStruggles #SpecialEducation #IEPTips #AdvocacyForKids #ParentEmpowerment #AutismSupport #EarlyIntervention #EducationMatters #AutismParents #AutismJourney #ChildAdvocacy #AutismAwareness #IEP #specialeducation

When should you use the term high functioning autism?  The majority of autistic people have been advocating for years to not use functioning labels. This is for a couple of important reasons. One being that we all have strengths and weaknesses just like anyone else. so we might be very "high functioning" in one area but need a lot of support in another.  The other reason is that functioning labels cause a lot more harm to the autistic community than they do good. often if someone is labeled low functioning, people just write them off and they often don't qualify for services that they might benefit from because of the low functioning label it is assumed they can't benefit from them. on the flip side of that, those who are considered high functioning, often still need a lot of support for certain things and are often denied help because "your functioning you don't need help you need to try harder" #autism #autistic #autismacceptance #autismawareness #autistictiktok #autisticcreator #functioninglabels

The story of autism luminary Temple Grandin 📖  Temple Grandin is a true inspiration for the autism community and beyond. Diagnosed with autism when it was barely understood, she overcame huge challenges and became a game-changer in animal science and autism advocacy. Temple’s work has helped break down myths about autism. Through her books and talks, she’s shown the world the importance of acceptance and inclusion. Her approach focuses on strengths and different learning styles, changing how we support people with autism. Let’s celebrate Temple’s amazing journey and her dedication to making the world better for everyone. Her story reminds us to embrace diversity and strive for a more inclusive society. 🫶  #actuallyautistic #autistic #autism #neurodiversity #neurodivergent #advocacy #spectrum #autismawareness #autisticmemes #autisticpride

Did you know screen time can have a negative effect on children? Electronic devices are so common nowadays and come so many different shapes and forms.  However, the screens can have negative impacts on the brain and circadian rhythms.  In this video, I wanted to talk about the effects of screen time, particularly in children less than four years old.  It’s a pet of mine when I see that young children having electronic devices and playing on them.  Another issue with these devices is that they are often held near the reproductive areas which is another cause for concern. If you do have a young one, please do not give them screens to play on. As you know Mikko stims a lot. Sucking her thumb and hair twirling is her go to for comfort. Even before we knew what Autism stimming was, This was always her thing since she was 3 months old. She didn’t quite like the pacifier and only really found comfort in her hands.  Thumb sucking can cause major dental issues with how her mouth is forming as she grows and because she is nonverbal, I fear that it can also hinder how she learns to communicates. Although this may be working at the moment, we are actively working toward a more permanent solution. Stimming is something that will naturally change as she grows, we just want to make sure it does not turn into a different unhealthy habit. #asd #autism #autismawareness #adhd #autismacceptance #specialneeds #autistic #autismmom #autismfamily #aspergers #autismspectrumdisorder #autismspectrum #autismsupport #autismlife #autismparents #autismlove #sensoryprocessingdisorder #differentnotless #neurodiversity #autismspeaks #autismdad #actuallyautistic #disability #autismo #anxiety #mentalhealth #downsyndrome #autismcommunity #love #autismadvocate

People who have Autistic Spectrum Disorder, formally known as Autism or Asperger's Syndrome can sometimes have difficulty learning what expressions and different body languages mean? This is a skill that can be learned! While I was never bothered social questions as an autistic kid myself…SO MANY of my clients are.  They just don’t find connection that way. 🤷🏼‍♀️ 📝 Through my 9 years of clinical experience supporting kids on the autism spectrum…here’s some things to try instead: ▪️ Use open body language to show you’re available ▪️Narrate/describe their actions ▪️Play with similar objects nearby  ▪️Follow the child’s lead ▪️Be responsive to their movements, sounds, and words ▪️Make STATEMENTS about what you see/hear/feel/think  #autistic #autism #aba #autismacceptance #autismawareness #therapist #neruodivergent #pda #autismmom #therapy

People with ADHD are more likely to have trouble with sensory processing in general, but auditory processing issues are especially common.  People with auditory processing issues don’t have any problem with their ability to hear. But things start to break down once the sound goes from ear to brain.  That means that even though we may physically hear what someone says, it may take us a while to actually process and understand it.  Studies have shown that people with ADHD are more likely to have trouble distinguishing between sounds and filtering out irrelevant sounds so they can focus on the important ones (for example, ignoring background noise in a restaurant so they can focus on a conversation). Interestingly, studies have suggested that treatment with stimulant medications may restore auditory processing abilities in some people with ADHD. If you have trouble with this stuff, you may be able to request that your school or workplace provide written instructions in addition to verbal. Most schools and workplaces are able to accommodate this and it can be really helpful! Note: we do not diagnose ADHD based on auditory processing issues alone. ADHD is not the only cause of auditory processing issues and not everyone with ADHD will have auditory processing issues. #adhd #adhdproblems #adhdmemes

What do you prefer?? 👟🛼🥾👠🙂❤️ I know it seems like such a little issue from the outside, but for someone that’s autistic or have sensory issues & anxiety, simple things like this can sometimes be a catalyst to bigger issues like sensory overloads or meltdowns, & burnouts.  I can tie knots and even do paragliding, so it’s not that I can’t figure it out. It’s the sensory aspect that I’m struggling with, and the anxiety of not knowing if I can count on it.  There can be several reasons to why someone might prefer velcros over normal shoelaces neurodivergent or not. And that’s more than okay 🙂👍.  It’s also fine to prefer a more sensory friendly approach when it comes to clothes and accessories and stuff that makes life easier 🙂👍. #shoes #spd #sensoryprocessingdisorder #sensoryprocessing #autism #autismawareness #fyp #adhd #anxiety #disability #disabled #autistic #autisme #autistictiktok #ashdlife

probably the biggest ✨aha✨ moment of my autism discovery process was realizing all the specific routines, rules, and workarounds I made around everyday activities to get around sensory differences (before I knew this was the reason why!)👀…and while not much has changed routine wise, it’s been a complete 180 in my own mind to not be so embarrassed by them! I have struggled for years trying to push through sensory discomfort, unable to advocate for my needs when I truly needed them. And honestly it’s still an ongoing challenge to unlearn the internalized ableism society has taught me and advocate for myself. But I’m constantly reminding myself, if it makes your life easier and doesn’t hurt anyone else, why wouldn’t you do it? 🩷 let me know what’s your most important sensory accommodation! 🌈 #accomodation #accomodations #disabilityawareness #disabled #sensoryprocessingdisorder #spd #sensoryissues #autismtraits #autismawareness #autism #autisticpride #stimming #autisticadults #unmaskingautism #actuallyautistic #latediagnosedautistic #audhd #autismmemes #autismmeme #neurodivergent #neurospicy #neurodivergentmemes #ausian

Tummy time challenge✨  Dont just place your baby on their tummy, instead support them at their hips and gently guide them over-encouraging them to do the upper  body work 💪🏻**Some babies may need more or less support. This is a great sensory activity (vestibular input), an awesome strengthening activity for the upper body+neck, and facilitates rolling! A great way to prepare them for future rolling skills! Visually tracking a toy from side to side is another super beneficial yet great challenge for the visual+sensory systems, and to address weakness and limited motion! ✨ *not medical advice #infant #infantdevelopment #babymilestones #occupationaltherapy #pediatricoccupationaltherapy #pediatrics #pedsotoftiktok #pedsot #milestone #babymilestones #baby #torticollis #torticollistreatment #torticollisbaby #plagio #plagiocephaly #plagiocephalyawareness #sensory #tummytime #tummytimeactivities #tummytimetips #tonguetie #tonguetiebabies

Across generations and within our Korean culture, parenting styles often followed an authoritative approach with punitive punishments considered the norm.  As a result, I've consciously chosen to embrace gentle and conscious parenting to break these generational cycles. Every day, I make a deliberate choice to be mindful and gentle with my son. I must admit that practicing these parenting approaches with Michael isn't very challenging, as he possesses an innate calmness and he’s incredibly sweet.  Even in moments when he tests his boundaries, his natural disposition makes the process smoother. Having said that, I want to dispel the stereotype that surrounds gentle parenting or conscious parenting. This approach doesn't mean the absence of boundaries or consequences. Instead, it signifies that boundaries and natural consequences are established and enforced with empathy and understanding, all with the ultimate aim of nurturing a healthy parent-child relationship. #cute #toddler #parenting #autism #signlanguage #nonspeaking #nonverbal #inspiration #motivate #autismawareness #autismjourney #neurodivergent

Anak sulung saya ni, umur 8tahun, diagnosed with Level 1 Autism Spectrum Disorder atau yg orang selalu sebut "Mild Autism". Dalam video ni, antara gejala autism yg anak saya ada. Dia tiba-tiba ketawa & happy tanpa sebab yg munasabah. Macam dalam video ni, kami just duduk rehat² dalam bilik je pun. Adalah tu benda yg dia teringat dalam kepala otaknya tu yg membuatkan dia tiba-tiba jadi happy & excited. 🤭 Doktor pakar anak saya kata, anak autistic memang ada yg bergejala macam ni. Otaknya tu akan replay & rewind balik kejadian-kejadian yg lepas, yg dia suka. Salah 1 contoh gejala yg terletak di bawah "tingkahlaku berulang". So, kalau anak ibu ayah kerap & berulang-kali buat perangai macam ni, better check, ok? 😊 p.s: Kalau rasa perkongsian saya ni bermanfaat, please LIKE, COMMENT & REPOST supaya perkongsian saya ni boleh sampai kepada lebih ramai ibu ayah di luar sana. 🥰 #autism #autismawareness #autismacceptance #kasihiautism #raikanautism #parenting #cikguanaksendiri

⏬¿Sabes por qué a las personas neurodivergentes el café y las bebidas con cafeína no las activan?⏬ Y no sólo no las activan sino que tienen en ellas un efecto calmante. Esto se produce porque al tener una química cerebral diferente, la cafeína les crea sensación de bienestar, te lo explico: A las  personas con un cerebro neurodivergente como autistas, altas capacidades o tdah, la cafeína actúa como un relajante que libera mayor cantidad de neurotransmisores como la dopamina y la noradrenalina que mejoran su atención y concentración, creando en ellos una sensación de bienestar y tranquilidad que les ayudan con la pesadez del día a día.  Pero, aunque esta sensación de bienestar se da en neurodivergentes, no todos la perciben de igual modo y las altas cantidades de cafeína pueden provocar ansiedad en ellos. #aacc #altascapacidades #tdah #tda #estudiar #dislexia #tecnicasdeestudio #examen #psicologia #atencion #concentracion #neurodiversidad #neurodivergente #mindfulnes #comoestudiar #psiquiatra #olvidar #memoria #recordar #comoestudiar #psicología Y a ti, ¿la cafeína te activa o te relaja?

Why Autism in Women Is Often Overlooked: Understanding the Differences in Diagnosis Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD) can be easier to diagnose in adults, but women often go undiagnosed or misdiagnosed due to differences in how autism presents. Here’s why: Men with autism tend to fit the more stereotypical patterns of ASD, making their diagnosis more straightforward. Their struggles with emotional literacy and special interests are often more obvious. Women, however, often have more subtle or hidden traits. They may appear to master emotional literacy better and their special interests may not stand out as much, leading to a missed diagnosis. Women on the spectrum tend to show more variation in their special interests, whereas men may gravitate toward specific industries or skill sets, making their autism more noticeable. Understanding these gender differences is crucial for improving the diagnosis and support of women with autism, who often face unique challenges in a world that doesn’t recognize their experiences as easily. Learn more about how autism presents differently in women and why these differences matter for proper diagnosis and support. #autisminwomen  #autismawareness  #Neurodivergent
